INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts (id, language, textvalue) VALUES (255, 'en-UK', 'Software Requirements Engineering (SRE) deals with the elicitation, analysis, specification, and validation of requirements, as well as their management throughout the software product lifecycle.Software requirements are generically defined as:a) The set of conditions/needs that the software must satisfy in order to achieve a specific objective;b) The constraints on its design and operation.The topics in this KA detail the systematic way in which Software Engineering should deal with Requirements. All the concepts that this area encompasses are used in the Software Life Cycle Process called "Software Requirements Analysis" which, although often associated with the early period of software development, is an activity that extends throughout the life cycle of a software product.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts (id, language, textvalue) VALUES (256, 'en-UK', 'Software Design is the process of defining the architecture, components, interfaces, and other characteristics of software, as well as the result of that process.As part of the software life cycle, it is a process in which requirements are analyzed to produce a description of the internal structure of the software that will serve as the basis for its construction. The result of this process describes the Software Architecture, i.e., how the software is decomposed and organized into components and the interfaces between those components.During the Design process, engineers produce various models that form a kind of blueprint (or diagram) of the solution to be implemented. These models can be evaluated to verify that they effectively meet the product requirements.Despite the similarity of the term, Software Design does not refer only to the construction of the graphical components of the software, this activity being only a small subpart of the much more comprehensive KA Software Design.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts (id, language, textvalue) VALUES (257, 'en-UK', 'Software Construction refers to the detailed creation of software through a combination of coding (also known as programming), verification, testing, and debugging. In other words, this KA details the set of skills that an engineer must possess in order to effectively and methodically build software artifacts.Software Construction is strongly linked to Software Design and Software Testing, since the construction, as a process, uses the artifacts resulting from the Design process and feeds the Testing process.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts (id, language, textvalue) VALUES (258, 'en-UK', 'Software Testing consists of the set of knowledge that a software engineer must master to perform software testing.As an activity, Testing consists of the dynamic verification that a program provides the expected behaviors for a finite set of test cases appropriately chosen from the domain of typically infinite executions.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts (id, language, textvalue) VALUES (259, 'en-UK', 'Software Maintenance is the set of activities necessary to provide effective software support. This presupposes a systematic modification of the software after its delivery/publication in order to correct errors, improve its performance or even changes/increments of functionality.Maintenance has become increasingly important now that companies are trying to get the most out of their software investment by extending the life of their software products.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts (id, language, textvalue) VALUES (260, 'en-UK', 'Software Configuration Management is the task of identifying the configurations of a software at distinct points in time with the aim of systematically controlling changes to it throughout its life cycle.With the use of tools such as version control and baselines (fixed set of configurations at a certain point in time), it is thus possible, on the one hand, in case of problems, to determine what was changed and by whom and finally to correct, and on the other hand, in case of software stability, to replicate its configuration in a controlled manner.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts (id, language, textvalue) VALUES (261, 'en-UK', 'Software Engineering Management is the application of management activities (such as planning, coordination, measurement, monitoring, control, and reporting) with the purpose of ensuring that software products and services are delivered effectively, efficiently, and for the benefit of stakeholders.Software project management encompasses a set of skills with a decisive impact on its systematic implementationAmong the different aspects that an engineer has to manage in a software project are the application of specific standards of the organization to which he belongs, human resources management (whether at the level of hiring, training, career progression), communication management with a team and cost management.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts (id, language, textvalue) VALUES (262, 'en-UK', 'The Software Engineering Process is the KA that concerns the work activities performed by a software engineer for the purpose of developing, maintaining, and operating software.Examples of these activities are requirements, design, construction, testing, and configuration management, among others.Software processes are specified with various objectives such as: facilitating human understanding, communication, and coordination; assisting in the management of software projects; measuring and improving software quality in an efficient manner; supporting process improvement and providing a basis for automatic support of process execution.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts (id, language, textvalue) VALUES (263, 'en-UK', 'Software Engineering Models and Methods are tools that impose structure on software engineering with the aim of making this activity systematic, repeatable, and generally more likely to be successful.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts (id, language, textvalue) VALUES (264, 'en-UK', 'Software Quality is the capability of a software product to satisfy the stated or implied needs under specified conditions, as well as the extent to which the software product meets the established requirements – the quality thus depends on how precisely the established requirements represent the needs, desires and expectations of the stakeholders.In short, Software Quality is the reflection of how well a software product meets the requirements of the same product.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts (id, language, textvalue) VALUES (265, 'en-UK', 'The Professional Practice of Software Engineering refers to the knowledge, skills and attitudes that a software engineer must possess in order to practice software engineering in a professional, responsible and ethical manner.Due to the increasingly widespread impact that software has on people''s lives, engineers must possess a set of professional and personal characteristics that allow them to carry out their activity in a consistently conscientious manner, resulting in the creation of software with known and reliable characteristics.Professional practice thus means a way of conducting a service with the aim of achieving a certain standard or criterion, not only in the process of carrying out the service but also in the final product of that same service.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts (id, language, textvalue) VALUES (266, 'en-UK', 'Software Engineering Economics deals with decision-making related to Software Engineering in a business context. This arises from the direct relationship between the success of a software product or service and good business management.Economics is the study of value, costs, resources and the relationship between them under a given context. In the discipline of Software Engineering as well, both the activities and the resulting software have economic attributes (they have costs, require resources and have value).Software engineering economics then provides a way to study the attributes of software and its processes in order to systematically relate them to economic measures with the aim of making better decisions about them.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts (id, language, textvalue) VALUES (267, 'en-UK', 'The Knowledge Area Computing Foundations deals with the development and operational environment in which software evolves and is executed - the computer. This occurs for the simple fact that software does not exist in a vacuum nor can it be executed without recourse to a computer - this together with its components are the core of the environment where the software runs.The discipline of Software Engineering is based on Computer Science and as such, its importance is absolutely invaluable and crucial for its body of knowledge. A software engineer needs knowledge about the computer: its hardware, software, types of computers, programming paradigms, computer networks, compilers, databases, etc.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts (id, language, textvalue) VALUES (268, 'en-UK', 'The Mathematical Foundations KA stems from the intrinsic link between the disciplines of Engineering and Mathematics. In Software Engineering, however, this connection exists more at the level of the essence of logic and reasoning and not so much arithmetic (about numbers).Mathematics is a discipline concerned with the formal study of systems. Its intervention at the level of software engineering has a direct influence on techniques for identifying a set of rules for reasoning in the context of systems under study. Its strands of language and logic are also important for describing mathematical proofs about certain problems and developing an algorithmic solution for them.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts (id, language, textvalue) VALUES (269, 'en-UK', 'Engineering Foundations is a KA that arises from the fact that Software Engineering is an Engineering discipline. As mentioned earlier, engineering is defined as "the application of a systematic, disciplined and quantifiable approach to structures, machines, products, systems or processes."It is the difference between this statement and another more empirical approach that allows Software Engineering to be recognized as a fully legitimate engineering discipline. As such, this KA addresses the aspects that apply to software engineering and other engineering disciplines, such as measurement, experimental techniques, or statistical analysis.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts (id, language, textvalue) VALUES (270, 'en-UK', 'No Software Engineering Knowledge Area');
