INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (474, 'en-UK', 'Covers the definition of a software requirement; the difference between a product requirement and a process requirement; the difference between functional and non-functional requirements; interdependent requirements; how to classify requirements quantitatively; and the difference between system and software requirements.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (473, 'en-UK', 'Covers the continuous nature of the requirements process and its adaptability to the context of the project or organization; the different actors in the process (often known as stakeholders); how to manage a requirements process and how to assess and improve its quality.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (472, 'en-UK', 'Covers the sources of requirements (such as domain knowledge, stakeholders, business rules, etc.) and the techniques for collecting them effectively (such as interviews, scenarios, prototypes, meetings, etc.).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (471, 'en-UK', 'Covers how to classify requirements according to their type, importance, stability, or scope; and conceptual modeling (such as use cases, data models, state models, etc.).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (470, 'en-UK', 'Covers the production of a set of documents on the requirements that can be systematically reviewed, evaluated, and approved. These documents are: the System Definition, the System Requirements Specification, and the Software Requirements Specification (derived from the system requirements).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (469, 'en-UK', 'Covers the techniques for validating the requirements gathered, such as: peer review, prototyping, model validation, and acceptance testing.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (468, 'en-UK', 'Covers the practical aspects of requirements; the iterative nature of the requirements process; the management of requirements changes (as a whole or in only some of their attributes); requirements traceability; and measurement of the weight of requirements in the event of a product change.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (467, 'en-UK', 'Covers the general concepts of design (such as objective, constraints, alternatives, context, etc.); the design process (difference between architectural and detailed design); and the principles of software design (such as abstraction, coupling, cohesion, decomposition, modularization, encapsulation, separation of interface and implementation, sufficiency, completeness, etc.).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (466, 'en-UK', 'Covers typical problems in software design such as concurrency: event control; data persistence; distribution of components and communication between them; error handling and fault tolerance; interaction and presentation; and security.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (465, 'en-UK', 'Covers the ways to organize software at various levels of abstraction from macro-architecture to detailed code design; the different architectural styles such as layered construction, distributed systems (Client-Server, Three-Tiers, Broker), interactive systems (Model-View-Controller, Presentation-Abstraction-Control), adaptable systems (microkernel or reflection), and others; Design Patterns (such as builder, factory, adapter; bridge, iterator, strategy, etc.); the decision-making aspect of the design process; and software program families and frameworks.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (464, 'en-UK', 'Covers effective communication with the software user; basic UI principles (ease of learning, familiarity, consistency, minimal surprise, diversity of use, etc.); dealing with common problems (user interaction and information presentation); typical interaction modes (question-and-answer, direct manipulation, menu selection, forms, command languages, natural language); how to present information (number of colors, color changes, color coding, visualization for people with special needs); the UI design process (user analysis, software prototyping, evaluation of the developed user interface); adapting the UI for localization and internationalization; and metaphors and conceptual models (such as using universally recognized icons for various common actions, such as using a scroll wheel to represent settings).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (463, 'en-UK', 'Covers the quality attributes of design (such as portability, testability, robustness, performance, security, reusability, etc.); quality assessment techniques (such as third-party design review, formal static analysis - with mathematical models - or informal, simulation or prototyping); and software metrics for its size, structure, or quality.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (462, 'en-UK', 'Covers the representation of design in different universally understood artifacts; structure descriptions (class and object diagrams, component diagrams, class responsibility cards, entity-relationship diagrams, interface description languages, etc.); and descriptions of behaviors and dynamics between components (activity diagrams, communication diagrams, data flow diagrams, decision tables and diagrams, sequence diagrams, state transition diagrams, pseudocode, etc.).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (461, 'en-UK', 'Covers how to design a system in one or more well-defined paradigms, such as Functional, Object-Oriented, Data-Structure-Centric, and Component-Centric; and general design strategies such as divide-and-conquer, top-down, bottom-up, etc.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (460, 'en-UK', 'Covers tools that help create software design artifacts, typically software itself, which can, for example, create models and diagrams or enable quality analysis of models.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (459, 'en-UK', 'Covers the fundamental concepts of software construction, which are: Minimization of Complexity, Anticipation of Changes, Construction for Verification, Reuse, and Construction Standards (relating to the conventions of the programming languages used, such as variable naming or indentation, etc.).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (458, 'en-UK', 'Covers how to manage a construction process through Life Cycle Models (such as linear Waterfall methodologies or iterative Agile types); construction planning (the order of activities in a construction process - this is highly dependent on the construction model used); and how to measure what is created (statistics on code, scheduling, effort - again, different measures depend on the model chosen, e.g. effort is a typical measure of the scrum methodology).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (457, 'en-UK', 'Covers the predominantly practical nature of construction; the need to make small-scale adjustments or modifications to the Design during construction; the languages needed to build software - such as configuration languages, scripting languages, programming languages, visual languages, etc.; the characteristics of coding itself (semantic constructs, control structures, error handling, organization of code into classes, ways of documenting code, etc.); construction tests (unit tests and integration tests); construction techniques for reuse by others (such as structuring libraries, using known design patterns); reuse of pre-existing software (use of libraries, public repositories, etc.); quality in construction (code testing, debugging, assertions, defensive programming, code reviews, etc.); and integration of code into a system (phase integration and incremental).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (456, 'en-UK', 'Covers how to design and use APIs; typical problems of object-oriented paradigms (such as polymorphism and reflection); parameterized and generic types; assertions, interface programming, and defensive programming; error handling; executable models (creating a program by compiling an executable model of a modeling language); state-based and table-based programming; runtime configuration and internationalization; language grammar processing; concurrency primitives (semaphores, mutexes, monitors, etc.); middleware (software that provides services between the OS layer and the application layer); programming for distributed systems; construction of heterogeneous systems (such as Digital Signal Processors or Embedded Systems); performance analysis and tuning (choices of architectures, data structures, or algorithm selection); platform standards (e.g. J2EE vs J2SE); and test-driven development.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (455, 'en-UK', 'Covers all kinds of tools (typically also software) that help with software construction, such as IDEs (integrated development environments such as Eclipse, Netbeans, Visual Studio, etc.); GUI builders (now also part of modern IDEs); unit testing tools, and also code profiling tools, performance analysis tools, and slicing tools.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (454, 'en-UK', 'Covers the fundamental concepts of testing; the distinction between fault, failure, error, and defect; test case selection; test effectiveness and objectives; testing for defect discovery; theoretical and practical limits of testing; impractical test scenarios; and the relationship of testing to other software lifecycle activities.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (453, 'en-UK', 'Covers the different levels at which software can be tested; by test target (unit testing vs integration testing vs system testing); by test objective (acceptance testing, installation testing, alpha and beta testing; reliability testing, regression testing, performance testing, security testing, stress testing, back-to-back testing, recovery testing, interface testing, configuration testing, and usability testing).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (452, 'en-UK', 'Covers the different techniques used to find the largest number of possible failures; techniques based on the Engineer''s Intuition (ad hoc and exploratory testing); techniques based on the input domain (equivalent partitioning, combinatorial testing, boundary value testing, random testing); techniques based on code (code control flow testing, data flow testing); techniques based on failures (error guessing, mutation testing); techniques based on usage (typical operational profile testing, user observation heuristics); techniques based on models (decision tables, state machines; formal specifications, workflow models); techniques based on the nature of the application (web application vs mobile application, etc.); and combination of the described techniques.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (451, 'en-UK', 'Covers the different metrics used to assess the quality of tests; program evaluation metrics (size metrics, typical failures for that type of software, fault density, reliability assessment, reliability growth models); and test execution evaluation metrics (total test coverage, fault introduction, mutation results).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (450, 'en-UK', 'Covers how to organize testing activities, strategies, and techniques into a controlled process; practical considerations (creating test guides, process organizers, creating test documentation, test-driven development, creating an independent or internal test team, effort and test estimates, defining test termination, test reuse, and using a test pattern); and testing activities (test planning, test case generation, training environment development, systematic test execution, evaluation of test results, recording of results over time, defect tracking).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (449, 'en-UK', 'Covers the tools, typically also software, that help in the selection, execution, and evaluation of tests.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (448, 'en-UK', 'Covers the basic concepts, terminology, and definitions of software maintenance; the specific role of a software maintenance engineer; maintenance needs (correcting faults, improving software design, adapting to new environments, etc.); software maintenance costs; software evolution as one of the purposes of maintenance; and the different categories of maintenance (corrective, adaptive, perfective, and preventive).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (447, 'en-UK', 'Covers the main problems that a software maintenance manager faces, such as technical issues (limited understanding of the software in question, testing a system under maintenance, impact analysis of the proposed maintenance, degree of modifiability of a system in production); issues related to the management of the maintenance process (aligning the software maintenance process with the objectives of the responsible organization, managing and motivating maintenance managers, outsourcing maintenance); maintenance cost estimates; and maintenance metrics.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (446, 'en-UK', 'Covers the life cycle of a maintenance phase (analyzing problems, implementing modifications, approving, discontinuing the product, migrating, etc.); and the activities exclusive to a maintenance engineer (analyzing the state of the software, support tasks, planning maintenance in terms of deadlines and scope of maintenance, managing the configuration of the software under maintenance, ensuring the quality of the software under maintenance).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (445, 'en-UK', 'Covers the techniques used to successfully maintain and/or update software; understanding the software code; techniques for systematic software modification (such as refactoring); software reverse engineering techniques; software migration techniques; and software discontinuation techniques and policies.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (444, 'en-UK', 'Covers the tools that help with software maintenance, such as software slicing tools (which isolate the parts to be modified), static and dynamic code analyzers; data flow and dependency analyzers; and reverse engineering tools.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (443, 'en-UK', 'Covers how to organize configuration management; the constraints imposed on the process; typical planning of a configuration management process (who is responsible, what is the project schedule, what tools are to be used, what configurations to provide to third parties, the potential interactions between the software to be controlled and external ones); documentation of configurations and their management and use as guidelines in an organization; ensuring the correct application of the organization''s configurations either through the application of metrics, own tools, or simple audits.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (442, 'en-UK', 'Covers the identification of the entities to be subject to configuration control, the relationships between them, how to define their versioning, rules for creating a baseline, policies for integrating a software item (a file, source code, visual resources, etc.) into configuration control; use and management of software libraries.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (441, 'en-UK', 'Covers the control of the normal flow of a software configuration change management process, such as change request, evaluation, and acceptance/rejection of the proposed change; implementation of the change and its tracking, and finally authorization of deviation (of the functionality to be changed) or waiver (idem).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (440, 'en-UK', 'Covers the recording and reporting of the evolution of the state of software configurations over time; how to capture the state of software items at each moment and how to report them to the organization.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (439, 'en-UK', 'Covers the process of scrutinizing software configurations to ensure that their operation is aligned with the specified requirements (as a whole or at the level of a specific baseline), the planned architecture/design, and is aligned with the documentation.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (438, 'en-UK', 'Covers how to organize the delivery of one or more software versions; how to execute a software build process (packaging, distributing different versions simultaneously, different production environments; delivering a complete software product (when to deliver based on the state of the software, what other deliverables are there - such as documentation and release notes).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (437, 'en-UK', 'Covers the types of tools used to support effective configuration management, such as version control tools, build tools, customer issue support tools, development team workspace control tools, issue-tracking tools, etc.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (436, 'en-UK', 'Covers how to determine and negotiate software requirements; feasibility analysis (assessing the ability to meet the requirements based on all the constraints that are subject to it - such as costs, technologies, human resources, policies, etc.); requirements review processes (what are the rules agreed with stakeholders to make any changes to the requirements).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (435, 'en-UK', 'Covers how to plan a software project; what software lifecycle model to use (such as waterfall, spiral, or agile methods) and what tools to use to ensure its application; choice of deliverables (documentation, installable software, etc.); cost, effort, and timing estimates; allocation of human resources to tasks; risk management (identification, impact analysis, prioritization of risk factors, development of risk mitigation strategies, etc.); quality management (definition of quality metrics, ensuring the application of quality control throughout the project).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (434, 'en-UK', 'Covers the application of planning to project development; application of the terms contracted with the software recipient (the client); application of the planned measurements and metrics; monitoring and adapting plans as the project progresses and in some cases abandoning the project; organizing and developing progress reports.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (433, 'en-UK', 'Covers the monitoring and periodic evaluation of the project against the objectives and customer satisfaction; determining customer satisfaction with the requirements; evaluation and review of the performance of the methods, tools, and resources applied in the project.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (432, 'en-UK', 'Covers the completion of the project in its entirety or at a milestone; determining the scope of "termination" either in whole or in part (e.g. a pre-agreed number of implemented requirements can be a phase termination as well as all agreed requirements and the respective documentation can be the total termination); project termination activities (such as archiving documentation, how long to keep documentation, updating project statuses, preparing "Lessons Learned" documents, etc.).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (431, 'en-UK', 'Covers the application of measurements at the project, process, and work product levels; establishment and encouragement of measurements (what are the measurements, what is the scope, application of measurements by teams, etc.); measurement process planning; application of measurements in the processes with all relevant data collected and documented; evaluation of measurements and application of corrections or improvements if necessary.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (430, 'en-UK', 'Covers the tools used to aid in the management of a software project (planning and monitoring the project status, risk management tools, communication tools, and measurement tools). These are also typically software.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (429, 'en-UK', 'Covers the definition of what a software process is and what it comprises; required inputs, transformative work activities, and generated outputs; decomposition of the process into work units; roles and responsibilities; techniques, tools, and notations; software process management, its efficiency for a project, and the impacts of changing it to another.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (428, 'en-UK', 'Covers the different categories of software development life cycle models; categories of software processes, such as primary processes (for software development, operation, and maintenance), support processes (for configuration management, quality control, verification, and validation), organizational processes (training, infrastructure management, portfolio management, etc.), inter-project processes (transversal to several projects); software life cycle models (predictive or linear models such as the waterfall model vs iterative models such as the spiral model vs agile development models such as scrum); adaptation of existing software processes to the needs of the project, organization, or technological developments.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (427, 'en-UK', 'Covers the monitoring of process performance and its potential modification to better meet the specific needs of the project or organization; the different models and methods (qualitative ones that are subject to expert judgment or quantitative ones that are performed based on metrics); iterative process improvement models (such as the Plan-Do-Check-Act); process assessment and scoring systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (426, 'en-UK', 'Covers the different measures and measurement techniques used for software processes; measures of process efficiency (such as effort measures, man-hours, man-days, monetary costs of the process or process phase) or of the product itself; the quality of the measures to be used for processes and products; the use of software with process analysis models that allow testing various parameters of the processes used and determining possible improvement points; quantitative process measurement techniques (direct measurement of number of defects, man-hours, among others, and respective analysis by statistical methods) and qualitative techniques (such as questionnaires or interviews).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (425, 'en-UK', 'Covers all kinds of tools related to software processes, such as BPMN diagrams, spreadsheets, UML diagrams, or even project management software.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (424, 'en-UK', 'Covers the general principles of software modeling, which are "Modeling the essentials", "Providing a perspective on the problem", and "Enabling effective communication"; the properties of models (completeness, consistency, and accuracy) and expression of models (concept of entity and relationship and their meanings according to the type of model); the syntax and semantics of modeling languages (textual or graphical); the concepts of precondition, postcondition, and invariants.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (423, 'en-UK', 'Covers the different types of models used for software; information models (which identify and define a set of concepts, properties, relationships, and constraints on data entities); behavioral models (identify and define the functions of the software to be modeled, common examples are state machines, flow control models, and data flow models); structural models (define the logical or physical composition of its different parts, examples of which are class diagrams, object diagrams, and package diagrams).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (422, 'en-UK', 'Covers the techniques of critical inspection of models by the engineer; completeness analysis; consistency analysis; accuracy analysis; traceability between requirements, models, and implemented functionality; analysis of interaction between models and functionality.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (421, 'en-UK', 'Covers the organized and systematic approaches to software development for a target computer; Heuristic Methods, which are based on experience and widely practiced by the industry (such as Structured Analysis methods that treat software as a hierarchical set of functions, Data Modeling methods that focus on the form and relationship of data for organizations whose main asset is precisely data, and Object-Oriented Methods, whose software is a set of objects that represent the real world, encapsulate data, and have behavior); Formal Methods that use a rigorous mathematical notation that allows software to be defined, refined, derived, and verified; Prototyping Methods whose purpose is to develop a small or incomplete part of the software (usually the least well understood) in order to refine it with critical input from the prototype; Agile Development Methods, characterized by short iterative developments with high participation of team members (methods such as Extreme Programming, scrum, or Cristal Clear).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (420, 'en-UK', 'Covers the general principles of what defines quality for stakeholders; the installation of a quality-oriented work culture and ethic; the value of developing quality software and the impact it has on its costs; characteristics and quality models at the process and product level; quality improvement techniques (such as Plan-Do-Check-Act, kaizen, or Quality Function Deployment); concepts of software for critical systems and the impact that quality has on these systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (419, 'en-UK', 'Covers the processes that ensure that software products, services, and life cycle models meet organizational quality and stakeholder satisfaction goals; software quality assurance; quality verification and validation; review and audit of software processes and products.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (418, 'en-UK', 'Covers the practical problems that have an impact on software quality: how requirements influence quality management, such as the type of system security, the physical environment, the project budget, the degree of dependence of the project (critical software implies a high quality process); the different types of software defects (computational error, human error, defect, fault, and failure); software quality management techniques, such as static techniques (source code analysis, design analysis, formal methods, etc.), dynamic techniques (code execution, simulation, debugging), software testing performed by individuals outside the development team to verify the software''s conformance to its specification; software quality measurement (using quality metrics, statistical analysis, trend analysis, etc.) with the purpose of having an overview of the product quality and its problematic parts.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (417, 'en-UK', 'Covers software quality process support tools, such as static code syntax and semantics analysis tools (such as compilers, Java Mission Control, etc.) and dynamic code analysis tools (such as debuggers).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (416, 'en-UK', 'Covers the engineer''s adherence to codes of ethics, professional conduct, and standard practices established by their professional community; accreditation, certification, and licensing; codes of ethics and professional conduct defined by their professional community (such as the ACM and IEEE codes of ethics); professional societies and their function (e.g., the IEEE or the Order of Engineers); software engineering standards (e.g., the IEEE''s many software engineering standards); the economic impact of software; the various types of employment contracts and characteristics; legal issues (such as trademarks, intellectual property, fair use, cybercrime, copyright); the creation of documentation and its procedures; negotiations (of requirements, functionalities, contracts, etc.).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (415, 'en-UK', 'Covers issues related to teamwork and different groups of individuals such as clients or collaborators; issues related to teamwork (intellectual honesty, admitting ignorance, admitting mistakes, adaptability); factors that affect personal cognition (volume of data, complexity of problems, inability to express problems, inability to consult with others, etc.); how to deal with complex problems (teamwork, problem decomposition, etc.); how to interact with stakeholders; dealing with uncertainty and ambiguity in development problems; dealing with multiculturalism issues in teams or clients.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (414, 'en-UK', 'Covers the engineer''s oral and written communication skills; reading technical material, comprehension, and summarization; writing skills for documents relevant to software processes (requirements, software documentation, contracts, etc.); effective communication with teams or groups; skills to create and deliver presentations (of ideas, products, pitches, etc.).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (413, 'en-UK', 'Covers the basic concepts of economics; finance and accounting; cost control; cash flow; decision-making processes (oriented to economics); concept of value; inflation and depreciation; taxation (taxes); time value of money (the fluctuation of the value of money over time); economic efficiency; effectiveness; definition of productivity.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (412, 'en-UK', 'Covers the economic concepts applied to software activity throughout its lifecycle; concepts of product, project, program, portfolio, product lifecycle, project lifecycle, proposals and types of proposals; investment decisions; planning horizon (on the economic costs related to investments in a certain period, such as the lifetime of a software product and its economic impact on a company); concept of price and establishment of pricing policies; concept of cost and cost management; measurement of economic performance; earned value management (an economic technique that allows effective cost control by comparing the value already created with the projected budget and the cost schedule up to that point); product termination decisions based on economics; replacement decisions (replacing an outdated software with a new one instead of maintaining it) or discontinuation (of a product or activity as a whole).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (411, 'en-UK', 'Covers the concepts of economic objective, estimates and planning; estimation techniques (such as analogies, part-by-part estimation, statistical methods, etc.); reacting to uncertainty (such as using estimates from different areas, postponing final decisions, etc.); prioritization techniques; decision-making techniques under risk (such as decision trees, Monte Carlo analysis, etc.); decision-making techniques under uncertainty (such as Laplace''s Rule, Hurwicz''s Rule, etc.).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (410, 'en-UK', 'Covers the different economic analysis methods applicable depending on the type of organization, purpose or objectives of the software: decision analysis for profit-making organizations; minimum acceptable rate of return (investment selection criterion based on a minimum percentage return); return on investment (ratio of value gained to invested); return on capital employed; cost-benefit analysis; cost-effectiveness analysis; break-even analysis (equality between costs and revenues); business case (structured and consolidated presentation of a business proposal from different decision perspectives such as costs, benefits, risk, etc.); multi-attribute evaluation (at the level of other properties than just money); optimization analysis.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (409, 'en-UK', 'The "Good Enough" principle (when the cost of adding a new feature - or investing in something non-essential - cannot be measured, this principle is an indicator of when the state of this feature is good enough to be delivered); frictionless markets (whenever there are barriers to perfect competition, be it transportation costs, establishments, protectionism and, particularly in software, internet non-neutrality or limitation of application sales in specific stores); ecosystems (when the qualities or attributes of a product are improved due to the existence of third parties that somehow interact with the product, such as an application that is integrated or configured to measure by an external company); offshoring (the development of an economic activity outside the organization''s operating territory for reasons of cost or quality deficits) and outsourcing (the execution of tasks for an organization by an external entity when these activities could be done by the organization).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (408, 'en-UK', 'Covers the definition of problem solving; problem formulation; problem analysis; designing a solution search strategy; problem solving using computer programs.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (407, 'en-UK', 'Covers the concepts inherent in abstraction - generically defined as "the process and result of generalization by reducing information to a concept, a problem, or an observable phenomenon in order to allow focus on the big picture"; levels of abstraction; concept of encapsulation; hierarchy of abstractions.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (406, 'en-UK', 'Covers the basic concepts of programming - the creation of computer programs using code; the programming process (design, writing, testing, debugging, and maintenance); the characteristics of different programming paradigms (unstructured, structured, procedural, imperative, object-oriented, functional, aspect-oriented, etc.).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (405, 'en-UK', 'Covers the languages in which it is possible to write code in order to create programs for a computer; the syntax and semantics of a language; low-level languages, high-level languages; differences between declarative and imperative languages.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (404, 'en-UK', 'Covers the process of finding and fixing problems in written software; the different types of errors (syntax errors, logical errors, data errors, etc.); debugging techniques (one step at a time, using breakpoints, using watchpoints, etc.); debugging tools (such as debuggers or static code analysis tools).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (403, 'en-UK', 'Covers the organization and forms of expression of data for use by programs; types of data structures (lists, queues, stacks, tables, hash tables, etc.); the different operations on different data structures (CRUD - create, read, update and delete, element finding operations, traversal, sorting).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (402, 'en-UK', 'Covers the organized writing of programs into algorithms - a strategy defined in a series of steps to solve a problem; attributes of algorithms (modularity, functionality, robustness, simplicity, etc.); algorithm analysis (worst-case analysis, average-case analysis, Big-O notation, etc.); algorithm design strategies (brute force, divide and conquer, greedy algorithms, dynamic programming, etc.); algorithm analysis strategies (step counting, asymptotic analysis, probabilistic analysis, etc.).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (401, 'en-UK', 'Covers the definition of a system; the properties of a system; emergent properties of a system; systems engineering and foundations of a computer system.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (400, 'en-UK', 'Covers the four levels of computer organization (macro-architectures, micro-architectures, logic circuits, and devices); digital systems (based on signals and binary code); digital logic (operations on binary numbers such as AND, OR, etc.); the expression of binary data in a computer; the central processing unit and its operation (CPU); memory organization; the operation of I/O devices.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (399, 'en-UK', 'Covers what a compiler is; the differences between compilers and interpreters; the compilation process.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (398, 'en-UK', 'Covers the concepts of an operating system; the tasks of an operating system; the different types of operating systems (batch, time-sharing systems, real-time systems, distributed operating systems, embedded systems, server operating systems, mobile operating systems, personal computer operating systems, etc.).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (397, 'en-UK', 'Covers the concepts of a database; entity and schema; the different database management systems (Oracle, MS SQL Server, Postgre, etc.); database query language - such as SQL - its features and how to use it; organization and manipulation of a database management system; data mining (the discovery of patterns and non-obvious relationships between data).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (396, 'en-UK', 'Covers the different types of networks (personal area network, local area network, wide area network, internet, etc.); the basic concepts of networks (their components and the different functions of these); network protocols and standards (OSI stack and its components such as TCP/IP, UDP, Bluetooth, etc.); the Internet; the Internet of Things; virtual private networks (VPN).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (395, 'en-UK', 'Covers the basic concepts of parallel computing and distributed computing; the differences between these two paradigms; parallel computing models (shared memory, message passing, etc.); the main problems in distributed computing.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (394, 'en-UK', 'Covers the typical problems that arise from the use of software by human users; considerations about I/O (such as how to show output to users, what is the most suitable format, what is the most pleasant way to present it, etc.); error messages (how to clearly explain what happened and how to solve it, what type of language, etc.); software robustness (how software tolerates incorrect use by people, how to recover in a way that does not discourage use by people, etc.).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (393, 'en-UK', 'Covers the common problems that arise from software being built and maintained by humans and how its writing affects these activities; how to structure code for easy understanding; how to write comments that make the work of present and future software owners easier.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (392, 'en-UK', 'Covers the practices and rules followed in order to make software more secure in all its phases, both at the requirements level and at the construction and testing level.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (391, 'en-UK', 'Covers the mathematical and logical concepts about sets (collection of elements), their properties and operations (intersection, union, Cartesian product, etc.); about relations (associations between two sets of information); about mathematical functions (a relationship of known behavior that expresses the mapping between elements of domains).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (390, 'en-UK', 'Covers propositional logic, its terminology and laws (Boolean variables, Boolean operations, Identity Laws, Distributive Laws, De Morgan''s Laws, etc.): Predicate logic, its properties, terminology and laws.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (389, 'en-UK', 'Covers the arguments that rigorously establish the truth of a statement; the methods of proving a theorem (proofs by contradiction, proofs by induction, etc.).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (388, 'en-UK', 'Covers the actions that allow finding the number of elements in a finite set of elements and its rules (sum rule, product rule, etc.) and principles; inclusion-exclusion principle; definition of recursion, randomness, probability, permutation and combination.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (387, 'en-UK', 'Covers the different types of graphs (directed graphs, undirected graphs, etc.), their terminology (vertices, nodes, weight, edges, etc.) and operations (traversal, connections, etc.); the different types of trees, their properties and operations (traversals, additions, etc.).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (386, 'en-UK', 'Covers the mathematical description of randomness, its terminology, properties and operations.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (385, 'en-UK', 'Covers finite state machines (the mathematical abstraction composed of a finite number of states and the transitions between them), their terminology and operations.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (384, 'en-UK', 'Covers the grammars of formal languages, their terminology (vocabulary, sentence, terminals, symbol, etc.); the existing types of grammars (context-free grammar, context-sensitive grammar, etc.).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (383, 'en-UK', 'Covers the problems that arise in the representation of numbers; the finite nature of the precision of number representation on a computer; rounding techniques; significant digits; types of errors (relative, absolute).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (382, 'en-UK', 'Covers numbers; the types of numbers (integer, rational, real, complex, imaginary, etc.); terminology and operations (division, mod, modulus); prime numbers, their usefulness and applications (such as cryptography).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (381, 'en-UK', 'Covers algebraic structures (defined as sets subject to some operations and satisfying a number of axioms); groups, their properties (associativity, identity, closure, etc.) and types (monoid, subgroup); rings (a set with two binary operations - usually addition and multiplication - where each operation combines two elements to form a third).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (380, 'en-UK', 'Covers how to propose solutions or solution models and conduct experiments to solve problems; creating controlled experiments (formulating hypotheses, creating preconditions, observing variables, relationship between results, etc.); observational study using contextualization; retrospective study, also known as historical study (analysis of historical data to find relationships between data and predict future events).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (379, 'en-UK', 'Covers the ability to achieve generalizable results by studying a limited population of samples of previous results (i.e. using statistics); the statistical concepts of sample, population, unit of analysis, random variable, event, distribution of variables, estimation, types of estimates, properties of estimators and statistical hypothesis testing; correlation and regression.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (378, 'en-UK', 'Covers the problem of measurement in software and its fundamental differences from other simpler measurement attributes; the concepts of levels (or scales) of measurement (nominal, ordinal, interval and ratio); direct versus indirect measures; reliability and validity of a measure; evaluation of reliability of measures.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (377, 'en-UK', 'Covers the challenges that the development of a structured solution to an engineering problem represents for the engineer, since in this case the design has nothing to do with its traditional concept - the graphical representation - but rather with the planning or architecture of a solution to a problem, its process and its phases (definition of a problem, obtaining relevant information, generation of multiple solutions, analysis and selection of a solution, implementation of the solution).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (376, 'en-UK', 'Covers the concepts and techniques of modeling (the process of representing part or all of a system using abstractions) and its different types (iconic, analogical and symbolic); the concept of simulation (conducting experiments on models in order to improve understanding of the model) and its construction; the concept of prototype (an initial, partial or incomplete representation of a system) and its use.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (375, 'en-UK', 'Covers the concept of standard (requirement, specification, guide or characteristic that must be observed by engineers so that products, processes and materials have acceptable levels of quality); the different types of standards that exist; measurable compliance with standards; the different entities that produce international engineering standards.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (374, 'en-UK', 'Covers the process of investigating and identifying how and why an undesirable event occurred and its root cause (i.e. what caused the event); the main techniques for conducting this type of analysis (review methods, present state vs desired state diagrams, third party review, failure trees, etc.); the tools to aid the analysis (cause and effect diagrams, histograms, Pareto charts, etc.).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (373, 'en-UK', 'For any topic in the program that does not fit into any of the Knowledge Areas.');
