INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (873, 'en-UK', 'Logic is the basis of all scientific reasoning and that is the main reason for its inclusion in the 1st year of the course. In addition, in the case of Computer Engineering, Logic has a direct operational interest in multiple dimensions of the profession.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (874, 'en-UK', 'This curricular unit introduces the principles of operation of a modern computer and its general architecture, with special emphasis on the contribution of each subsystem to overall performance. The analysis of the physical implementation technology of computers (logic and memory circuits), associated with the explanation of the elementary forms of information representation in digital format, will allow students to identify and describe fundamental principles of the operation of computers, programming languages and software development.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (875, 'en-UK', 'Objectives: Develop algorithms for solving problems using a structured approach; Select and create the appropriate abstractions, both at the level of procedures and data; Use the Scheme language as a development tool, characterized by a simple syntax.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (876, 'en-UK', 'Acquisition of theoretical and practical knowledge about differential and integral calculus in R that enable the application of the basic tools of mathematical analysis to the treatment and resolution of problems most adapted to the profile of the course. Enable the student to innovate, complementing knowledge to develop solutions to solve new questions.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (877, 'en-UK', 'This course has two fundamental objectives: on the one hand, being a propaedeutic course, it has a didactic/scientific character, promoting the development of logical reasoning and methods of analysis and, on the other hand, it aims to introduce and develop in theoretical terms a set of concepts that will be essential tools to support the more specific courses of Engineering.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (878, 'en-UK', 'Objectives: Welcome and integrate newly arrived students into the FEUP environment; Introduce the main services available on campus; Provide initial training in the areas known as “Soft Skills” (teamwork, communication, etc.) and raise awareness of their importance throughout the engineering career; Discuss scientifically a Theme/solve a Project of limited difficulty in the areas of engineering.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (879, 'en-UK', 'This course aims to: Ensure that students acquire an integrated view of concepts and basic techniques of Statistics in the context of the Computer Engineering course.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (880, 'en-UK', 'The main objectives of this curricular unit are to provide students with: - fundamental knowledge about procedural programming and object-based programming; - the ability to apply these programming paradigms to develop programs, using the C++ language as a tool.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (881, 'en-UK', 'The objective of this curricular unit is to give the student basic knowledge of mechanics and the computational methods used to solve dynamic systems. A Computer Algebra System (CAS) is used to allow the student to solve practical problems of mechanics and dynamic systems, instead of wasting a lot of time learning abstract methods. The knowledge acquired in dynamics and modeling of physical systems on the computer will be quite important in other curricular units related to computer graphics and visualization, game theory, simulation and scientific computing.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (882, 'en-UK', 'The curricular unit has two fundamental objectives: on the one hand, being a propaedeutic curricular unit, it has a didactic/scientific character, promoting the development of logical reasoning and methods of analysis and, on the other hand, it aims to introduce and develop in theoretical terms a set of concepts that will be essential tools to support the remaining curricular units.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (883, 'en-UK', 'The Microprocessors and Personal Computers curricular unit aims to develop, combine and apply in an integrated way concepts from the areas of Computer Architecture and Programming Languages. On the one hand, the curricular unit explores the relationships between the CPU instruction set and low-level programming (assembly language). On the other hand, recognizing that the architecture of modern personal computers goes far beyond the CPU architecture, the curricular unit will address the general architecture of a PC, including the data storage subsystem and other peripherals.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (884, 'en-UK', 'To prepare students in topics related to computer theory, with a special emphasis on topics related to formal languages. To enable students to express computational problems using formal languages, automata and Turing machines.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (885, 'en-UK', 'The course aims to first provide students with solid skills in numerical calculus. It will be organized by topics, covering the problems of numerical representation, the resolution of equations and systems of algebraic and differential equations, definite integration, non-linear optimization and curve fitting.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (886, 'en-UK', 'This curricular unit aims to provide students with basic knowledge of electromagnetism and signal processing. The approach is experimental, using simple experiments that students can carry out during the theoretical-practical classes to consolidate theoretical knowledge and acquire experience in using measurement instruments. The Computer Algebra System (CAS) used in the Physics 1 curricular unit is also used to facilitate the resolution of problems and to visualize electric and magnetic fields.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (887, 'en-UK', 'Following the curricular units of Introduction to Programming, the objective of this curricular unit is to: use the programming notions already established and systematize the use of information structures and algorithms to solve categories of problems; use object orientation as a paradigm to support program development; emphasize the organization of programs around abstract data types. Small projects will be carried out using the C++ language.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (888, 'en-UK', 'The objectives of the curricular unit are to provide students with the essential knowledge to be able to: - use the hardware interface of the most common peripherals of a PC; - develop low-level software and embedded software for the PC platform; - use the C programming language in a structured way; - use various software development tools.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (889, 'en-UK', 'This is an introductory course on databases. It covers the relational paradigm. It covers the design (UML model), construction (SQL data definition language), query (SQL data manipulation language) and management (optimization, access control and concurrency policies) of relational databases. It also introduces the concept of multi-dimensional databases, NoSQL databases and semi-structured data models.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (890, 'en-UK', 'This Curricular Unit aims to complement and deepen the knowledge acquired in the disciplines of "Programming" and "Algorithms and Data Structures", namely by introducing techniques for the design and implementation of efficient algorithms for solving different types of problems, as well as their analysis and evaluation.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (891, 'en-UK', 'To transmit knowledge of concepts, techniques, algorithms, technologies and architectures of Computer Graphics. - To reinforce theoretical knowledge with its practical application, through the implementation, testing and evaluation of algorithms covered in theory.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (892, 'en-UK', 'The main objectives of this curricular unit are to provide the fundamental knowledge about: - the structure and operation of an operating system; - the use of the programming interface (API) of a real operating system.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (893, 'en-UK', 'To develop and deepen object-oriented programming skills, in a modern object-oriented language (Java), representative of the languages used for application software development. To develop object-oriented design skills, using the UML language and applying good design principles and patterns. To learn how to develop applications with a graphical interface and to use extensive libraries. To acquire the habit of following good software development practices (iterative development, unit testing, debugging, refactoring, SCV, pair programming, etc.).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (894, 'en-UK', 'To acquire familiarity with the paradigms of Logic Programming and Constraint Programming. To develop the skills of abstract reasoning and problem representation in a declarative way.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (895, 'en-UK', 'This curricular unit has the main objective of developing a set of practical skills, some of which have already been addressed in previous curricular units in a more theoretical context. It focuses on practical development work, which is tendentially multidisciplinary, namely in the areas of Computer Graphics and Interfaces, Logic Programming and Operating Systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (896, 'en-UK', 'At the end of the curricular unit, students should be able to: - describe the principles, concepts and practices of software engineering and the software life cycle; - know and be able to apply the techniques and tools necessary to execute and manage the various activities of the quality software development process; - explain the methods and processes for building different types of software systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (897, 'en-UK', 'Computer Networks (RCOM) is the curricular unit that introduces students to the knowledge domain of communication networks. The fundamental concepts addressed in RCOM include the following: communication channels and data link control, error and delay models, multi-access communications, routing, flow control and congestion control. The main technologies discussed in RCOM are switched Ethernet, Wireless LAN 802.11, the Internet and the TCP/IP communications stack. The implementations and projects to be developed in RCOM include a data link protocol with flow control, an application running in client mode, and the configuration and testing of Ethernet and IP networks.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (898, 'en-UK', 'The aim of this course is for students to develop skills in the most significant WEB languages and technologies, in the current technological context, or that were decisive in the evolutionary process of the WEB.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (899, 'en-UK', 'The LBAW curricular unit aims to consolidate the material presented in the curricular units of databases and web languages and technologies. This curricular unit offers a practical perspective on two central areas of computer engineering. In this curricular unit, the aim is to provide students with the ability to design and develop information systems accessible through the web and supported by database management systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (900, 'en-UK', 'This curricular unit presents a set of core topics for the area of Intelligent Systems. Its objectives are: - To know what characterizes and distinguishes AI and its applicability. - To know how to Represent, Acquire, Manipulate and Apply Knowledge using Computational Systems. - To develop a small project using AI techniques.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (901, 'en-UK', 'To provide the concepts that allow: - to understand the compilation phases of languages, especially imperative and object-oriented languages; - to specify the syntax and semantics of a programming language; - to understand and use the data structures and main algorithms used in the implementation of compilers.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (902, 'en-UK', 'This curricular unit has two fundamental objectives: to provide students with theoretical knowledge about distributed systems so that they can make correct decisions when faced with the need to implement a system of this nature; to provide students with practical knowledge so that they can develop and take advantage of distributed systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (903, 'en-UK', 'To identify and acquire the essential knowledge to know how to progressively maximize the conditions for successful personal and interpersonal performance. To be aware of the importance of knowing how to use complementary skills (soft skills) and of making evolutionary changes in order to develop a professional profile that contributes to continuously improving the future activity of the computer engineer.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (904, 'en-UK', 'Interpret, Classify and Explain:\n- Sales and Procurement Process managed by an ERP;\n- how the IS contributes to Value Construction in an organization, with special focus on ERP and others with which the ERP integrates (e.g.: manufacturing execution system and warehouse management);\n- Technological trends and their impact on business information systems (Cloud Computing, Big Data, the new Internet).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (905, 'en-UK', 'Objectives: to equip students to be able to define and apply a software development process, using agile practices, typical software development tools, in a team.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (906, 'en-UK', 'The curricular unit aims to develop skills in the area of Management, integrating a solid theoretical component, based on the presentation and discussion of concepts and methodologies, with its application to the analysis and discussion of case studies.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (907, 'en-UK', 'The curricular unit assumes itself as Engineering (evidencing only the essential theory to understand the practical applications) and provides a global perspective of the techniques associated with the specification and development of Computational Agents as well as highlights its practical relevance presenting examples of application.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (908, 'en-UK', 'To develop abstraction skills in order to describe what the system should do and not how to do it. To be familiar with formal methods and how they can contribute to increasing the quality of software systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (909, 'en-UK', 'To provide students with the skills to: - identify decision problems; - apply the various phases of solving a decision problem, in particular, the definition and structuring of problems, the construction of models and the use of quantitative methods to obtain the solution; - critically analyze the solution obtained; - understand the importance of the role of change agent in organizations.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (910, 'en-UK', 'At the end of the Curricular Unit, students should be able to: - Identify the need for project management and the importance of its strategic framework; - Identify the different normative references and methodologies for project management; - Identify and define the process areas and variables of project management; - Apply project management and teamwork methodologies and tools; - Apply quality management concepts and tools to projects; - Identify and manage the risks inherent in a project.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (911, 'en-UK', 'The Software Systems Architectures course has the main objective of introducing the concepts of software architectures, design patterns and directly related topics, such as software components.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (912, 'en-UK', 'This curricular unit aims at providing students with skills in the planning and integrated management of network infrastructures, systems and services.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (913, 'en-UK', 'Acquisition of knowledge leading to the simultaneous use of several processing units in a computing system. Building a solid foundation on parallel architectures, algorithm parallelization, programming models, process synchronization and performance measurements, through the development of programs.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (914, 'en-UK', 'This CU discusses the fundamental aspects of the operation of mobile communications networks, the most important mobile communications technologies, and engineering and design techniques for mobile communications networks.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (915, 'en-UK', 'The objective of this curricular unit is to transmit knowledge about the process of developing computer games, with particular emphasis on the aspects related to the programming of the various modules that make up a game engine.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (916, 'en-UK', '');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (917, 'en-UK', 'To provide students with the skills to plan, manage and carry out a process of analysis and specification of requirements for a software system.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (918, 'en-UK', 'This curricular unit focuses on obtaining annotation languages for a given domain and on carrying out applications based on annotation languages and has the following objectives: - To raise awareness among students of the multiple non-trivial applications of annotation languages; - To familiarize students with the technologies for processing and storing semi-structured information; - To apply annotation technologies in the definition of a language and in the resolution of a problem by developing an application.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (919, 'en-UK', 'The curricular unit aims to develop skills in the area of Marketing Management, integrating a solid theoretical component, based on the presentation and discussion of concepts and methodologies, with its application to the development of a marketing plan and the discussion of case studies.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (920, 'en-UK', 'The objectives of the course are: - To present the basic concepts of (computer) modeling and simulation and its various application areas; - To present the main phases of the life cycle of a simulation project, from the modeling phase to the analysis and application of results; - To present the main types of models and their adequacy to deal with different problems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (921, 'en-UK', 'The objectives of the curricular unit are: a) to present the concepts, services and multimedia and hypermedia applications; b) to present the techniques of coding and representation of multimedia information; c) to introduce the development tools of applications; d) to develop applications.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (922, 'en-UK', 'This Curricular Unit aims at studying the security issues of Computer Systems, in order to provide students with a basic overview of the concepts and threats and defenses against abusive and destructive use of such systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (923, 'en-UK', 'This CU aims to provide students with the ability to develop embedded systems with real-time requirements, using, if necessary, real-time operating systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (924, 'en-UK', 'This CU aims to enable students to develop and administer large databases, namely to tune the physical schema, to optimize SQL queries, to take advantage of object manipulation extensions and XML technology, and to retrieve and replicate data.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (925, 'en-UK', 'The main objectives of the curricular unit include: - the acquisition of knowledge and practice of the essential concepts of the project and architecture of enterprise distributed applications; - application of the main patterns and technologies, according to the requirements and functionalities of the final scenarios; - detailed knowledge of various technologies, with a view to their fluent implementation, and their interoperability and integration.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (926, 'en-UK', 'The curricular unit "Dissertation Preparation" accompanies the process of organization and preliminary work of the dissertation of the Master in Integrated Engineering in Computer Engineering and Computing. Students complete PDIS before the semester in which the dissertation is carried out full-time. The effort of the unit is equivalent to 6 ECTS (1/5 of full-time semester) and is occupied with the choice and familiarization with the dissertation topic, with the study of the state of the art in the dissertation domain and with the realization of preliminary work that allows in the semester of the dissertation an intense, well-focused work with good presentation of results.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (927, 'en-UK', 'Individual research and development work, leading to the elaboration of a dissertation of a scientific nature on a topic in the knowledge area of the course, or aiming at the integration and application to the resolution of complex engineering problems of knowledge, skills and attitudes acquired throughout the course.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (928, 'en-UK', 'The objective of this course is to provide students with the knowledge of the basic methodologies for the analysis of the economic and financial feasibility of investment projects.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (929, 'en-UK', 'The objective of the Data Warehouse CU is to provide students with the ability to design, implement and explore data warehouses.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (930, 'en-UK', 'The main objectives of this curricular unit aim at the acquisition of knowledge and practice of the essential concepts of the project, architecture and implementation of applications, mainly business, in mobile devices, using widely used APIs.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (931, 'en-UK', 'The curricular unit "Information Description, Storage and Retrieval" aims to: - Raise awareness among students of the problems of storing and organizing large collections of data; - Familiarize students with the main concepts in text document retrieval and its application in tools; - Explore the methods and tools for describing resources on the web and for using the description in applications that make use of the meaning of the data.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (932, 'en-UK', 'The objectives of this CU are: - To motivate the use of knowledge extraction (EC) techniques from data, or data mining, in support of decision making. - To develop the ability to use these techniques correctly for the automatic analysis of large amounts of data.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (933, 'en-UK', 'The main objective of the course is to prepare students to analyze and design the interactive components of systems, in particular the user interface, in a way that is appropriate to their needs, considering the short, medium and long term.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (934, 'en-UK', 'The main objectives of the curricular unit are to provide students with knowledge and concrete experience in the definition, use and refinement of agile processes for the specificity of a project.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (935, 'en-UK', 'Augmented Reality is a technology that aims to improve or augment a user''s view of the real world with virtual images, using Computer Vision and Computer Graphics/Virtual Reality techniques. The main objective of this course is to transmit to students a set of basic knowledge of these techniques, which will allow them to pursue more advanced studies in the emerging field of Augmented Reality, and the ability to carry out small illustrative works of the methodologies studied.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (936, 'en-UK', 'The main objectives of the Robotics CU are: - To understand the basic concepts of Robotics and the framework of Artificial Intelligence in Robotics. - To study methods of perception and sensory interpretation (with emphasis on computer vision) - To study the fundamentals of cooperative robotics and robot team building - To analyze the main national and international robotic competitions, the most realistic robotic simulators and the most advanced robotic platforms available on the market.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (937, 'en-UK', 'This Curricular Unit aims at studying the security issues of Computer Systems, in order to provide students with a basic overview of the concepts and threats and defenses against abusive and destructive use of such systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (938, 'en-UK', 'The fundamental objective of this curricular unit is to learn, discuss and design solutions to the various problems that arise from the influence of software engineering (and the use of software in general) on people and society as a whole.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (939, 'en-UK', 'This Seminar has as main objectives: - To learn about and discuss ongoing research work in the areas of Intelligent Systems. - To make contact with different researchers in Intelligent Systems and, through them, with various research groups active in the topics presented.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (940, 'en-UK', '(Not available)');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (941, 'en-UK', 'The objective of this curricular unit is to provide students with consolidated knowledge in the area of computer networks from a perspective of network designers and managers, namely, the constitution of several subnetworks to meet specific requirements of organizations and users, assignment of IP address ranges, management of packet forwarding services within and between domains, identification of necessary network services, their installation and configuration.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (942, 'en-UK', 'Computer vision is an area of computer science focused on the extraction of "useful information" from images and videos. The goal of computer vision is to "discover from images what is present in the world, where things are located, what actions are being performed" (Marr,1982).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (943, 'en-UK', 'To provide students with the basic knowledge of Differential and Integral Calculus for real functions of one real variable. To be able to solve differential equations and apply the knowledge acquired in modeling and solving problems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (944, 'en-UK', 'A course in discrete mathematics has several objectives. Students should learn a set of mathematical facts and how to apply them; but, more importantly, they should learn to think mathematically. To this end, mathematical reasoning and the different ways of approaching and solving problems are emphasized.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (945, 'en-UK', 'To learn the basic principles of programming and data management in a problem-solving context. The algorithmic and modeling and data manipulation aspects are explored, and context about computer systems in general is also introduced.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (946, 'en-UK', 'It aims to give a general overview of the various areas of computer science. The practical component focuses on the application of digital electronics concepts used in the design of computers.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (947, 'en-UK', 'To provide students with the basic knowledge of Linear Algebra and Analytic Geometry. In particular, to solve systems of linear equations; to perform algebraic operations with matrices, to understand and relate fundamental concepts and results of vector spaces, to determine orthogonal projections and to understand their importance in the context of mathematical optimization, to understand and handle the concepts of eigenvalue and the spectral decomposition of a matrix');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (948, 'en-UK', 'The main objective is to provide students with the basic knowledge of Differential and Integral Calculus for functions of several real variables and Complex Analysis. To be able to solve linear differential equations with constant coefficients (using Laplace transforms) and difference equations (using Z transforms) and apply this knowledge in modeling and solving problems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (949, 'en-UK', 'To provide the student with a global notion of the functioning of a computer system, from the perspective of the programmer and the designer of digital systems, with special emphasis on: (i) knowledge about current computer architectures and the compromises that must be taken into account in the development of a computer system; (ii) programming in Assembly language; (iii) understanding of how software interacts with hardware and consequent consolidation of programming skills in C language.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (950, 'en-UK', 'To introduce basic knowledge in modeling standard behaviors of random phenomena in Engineering or Science contexts, contributing to a training capable of describing, analyzing and interpreting real situations through non-deterministic mathematical models.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (951, 'en-UK', 'To allow the student to acquire a set of solid knowledge about procedural programming using the C language, with particular emphasis on pointers and simple dynamic data structures.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (952, 'en-UK', 'To transmit to students basic concepts and working tools that allow them to explain, understand and predict phenomena in Classical Physics and Quantum Physics and their relation to Quantum Computing');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (953, 'en-UK', 'The Computer Networks course aims to provide students with a broad spectrum of knowledge in the areas of communications and the ability to design high-potential technical solutions.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (954, 'en-UK', 'The objective of this course is to give the student a set of solid knowledge in Object Oriented Programming. This knowledge will not be limited to the syntax of a particular programming language, but will include aspects related to object oriented modeling, as well as its graphical representation.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (955, 'en-UK', 'The objective of this course is to introduce students to the functioning of modern OSs and at the same time to provide students with the necessary skills to develop system applications that make direct use of the operating system programming interface and that exploit the capabilities of concurrency and multi-programming.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (956, 'en-UK', 'To study the different types of automata (finite, stack, Turing Machines) and formal grammars (regular, independent and context-dependent, recursive) and the relationships between them, as well as their relationship with programming languages and compilers.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (957, 'en-UK', 'To provide systematically the fundamental notions of information theory and its application in contexts of computational learning, data analysis and, above all, to the principles of coding in the contexts of source and channel coding and in cryptography.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (958, 'en-UK', 'After completing the curricular unit, the student must demonstrate knowledge and understanding in the following aspects: complexity analysis; general algorithm design techniques; data structures and sorting algorithms (characteristics, memory occupied, execution speed).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (959, 'en-UK', 'The course aims to develop the following skills:\n - Understanding and interpretation of phenomena and dynamic processes of the real and virtual world\n - Data analysis capacity supported by computational tools\n - Deepening of mathematical reasoning for information extraction\n - Ability to solve concrete problems in the context of the analysis and transformation of uni and multidimensional data in the time, space and frequency domain');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (960, 'en-UK', 'After completing the curricular unit, the student must demonstrate to have acquired, understood and know how to apply the knowledge and skills in:\n i) multimedia project\n ii) multimedia fundamentals\n Namely:\n - planning, design, development and management of multimedia projects in a team;\n - usability topics and their application in multimedia projects;\n - digital image, audio and video, with focus on the physiological and perceptual aspects involved and in the representation and compression of these types of multimedia data.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (961, 'en-UK', 'The main objectives of the course are the study and understanding of the protocol aspects of modern communication systems, with special emphasis on the Internet protocol environment, in view of a knowledge of the main issues that characterize and condition services and applications.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (962, 'en-UK', 'This is a cross-cutting discipline, with a vast field of application. One of the fundamental objectives is the acquisition of a set of knowledge and skills that allow, in a specific situation, to develop a simulation model, implement it, validate it and use it correctly, taking into account the advantages and limitations of the use of simulation.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (963, 'en-UK', 'This CU focuses on the fundamentals of relational databases, including relational model, normalization, relational operations, SQL language, transactions and concurrency control, indexing, etc. In addition, it also aims to operationalize these concepts through the analysis, design and practical construction of relational databases in a client-server environment.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (964, 'en-UK', 'By the end of the semester, students will be able to:\n(i) use different forms of communication in academic and professional contexts (e.g., writing a report);\n(ii) argue, using different codes, on social issues related to the profession (e.g., formal presentations);\n(iii) adapt their forms of communication to the target audiences (e.g., technical and popular texts).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (965, 'en-UK', 'The student should be able to understand why the complexity of software requires an engineering approach and the different ways of organizing people and activities for the development of a quality product, namely linear, iterative and incremental approaches. They should also be able to understand the differences between them and choose the most appropriate one(s) according to the specific context of the project. They should also be able to use generic project management techniques and artifacts (Gantt and PERT/CPM charts, risk analysis, etc.). Finally, they should be able to describe the software artifact to be developed using the UML language.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (966, 'en-UK', 'In this course, students will be made aware of the importance of certain concepts, principles and practices of innovation management, while becoming familiar with some methodologies and tools that allow their operationalization and implementation on the ground.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (967, 'en-UK', 'Students should acquire skills in the development of distributed applications using various technologies and should be able to understand and interconnect knowledge about fundamental techniques for designing distributed applications in a business environment and for the Internet.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (968, 'en-UK', 'The student should be able to understand: the objectives and architecture of a compiler; the principles of lexical, syntactic and semantic analysis and be able to implement these phases of a compiler, either from scratch or using appropriate tools; some principles of code generation.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (969, 'en-UK', 'In this curricular unit, it is intended that the student acquires knowledge about central topics in Computer Graphics, both at the level of fundamentals and at the level of use of graphic tools.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (970, 'en-UK', 'It is intended that the student acquires solid basic knowledge about the area of artificial intelligence at the level of fundamentals, techniques and practical application. For this purpose, the integrating concept of Agent is adopted. The development of agents of increasing complexity and capacity is studied following three metaphors: Symbolic, Connectionist and Biological.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (971, 'en-UK', 'Solving advanced problems typical of programming. Mostly practical classes.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (972, 'en-UK', 'This curricular unit provides students with the skills and tools that allow them to discuss the design and evolution of information systems (IS) with business stakeholders. Upon completing the course, students will understand the different and often contradictory perspectives of business stakeholders and IT professionals, thus becoming privileged interlocutors to help both parties plan the organization''s IS.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (973, 'en-UK', 'The objectives of this course are to stimulate the creation of entrepreneurship and innovation skills and to familiarize future professionals with the reality of the business fabric and the theoretical foundations of the creation and management of small businesses and businesses with a view to value creation.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (974, 'en-UK', 'Through this curricular unit, students will become familiar with the fundamental concepts for understanding the interaction between humans and computer systems. The student should:\n - understand the role of human factors in interaction and interface;\n - understand and apply prototyping techniques for research and testing of design proposals;\n - develop the ability to design interaction and interface design proposals for specific contexts of use with a view to optimizing the interaction experience, based on contextual and participatory approaches;\n - develop the ability to evaluate usability with mastery of various techniques and their adequacy to the project context;\n - develop the ability to build innovative and coherent interfaces with the purpose;\n - develop the ability to combine techniques systematically in an empirical approach to interaction design;\n - develop the ability to learn autonomously in the field of HCI.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (975, 'en-UK', 'To provide the experimental methods necessary to carry out empirical performance evaluation of computer systems that arise in the various areas of computer science, from communication networks to algorithms and artificial intelligence. Acquisition of skills at the level of analysis and synthesis, organization and planning.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (976, 'en-UK', 'This course focuses on models for system analysis, with emphasis on optimization problems and discrete event systems, with applications to the four thematic options of the course. It is intended that students will be able to:\n 1) formulate optimization problems, categorizing them according to their characteristics and formalizing them so that they can be solved by the most appropriate methods\n 2) model and analyze simple traffic, production, computational (hardware and software) and communication systems as discrete event systems\n Students should also develop skills in analysis and synthesis, problem solving, critical thinking, autonomous learning, and the ability to apply the theoretical knowledge acquired to concrete practical situations.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (977, 'en-UK', 'The main objectives of this curricular unit are the study of the fundamentals of transmission and switching systems. Topics include: modulation and signal transmission, transmission and switching systems, signaling aspects in digital systems. This curricular unit deals with the aspects of systems related to fixed or mobile and satellite networks, and with the transmission of voice and video signals. The curricular unit also covers the fundamentals of communication protocols related to error control, flow control and protocol specification.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (978, 'en-UK', 'The main objectives of the curricular unit are, on the one hand, the approach and study, theoretical and practical, of the main aspects related to the mobility of systems and networks and, on the other hand, the exploration of protocols, technologies and applications of sensor networks.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (979, 'en-UK', 'In this curricular unit, students will study different methods to understand the problem they are facing, the factors that condition the range of possible solutions, and the approaches to decide between these alternatives.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (980, 'en-UK', 'In this course, we address multiple structured ways of integrating applications, not only at the level of an organization, but beyond it. A strong emphasis is given to integration using middleware, in particular, using approaches such as SOA (Service Oriented Architecture) and ESB (Enterprise Service Bus).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (981, 'en-UK', 'To study the main computational learning techniques in the context of the multiplicity of data types available in the relevant applications, namely the development and interpretation of decision trees, configuration and training of artificial neural networks, fuzzy logic, fuzzy and neuro-fuzzy systems, and configuration and training of support vector machines. To develop the skills to design classification systems for large data sets, diagnostics in industrial and medical contexts, intelligent control, systemic analysis of complex problems and critical evaluation of results.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (982, 'en-UK', 'To provide students with the concepts, principles and advanced theories necessary for the development of real applications involving agents or systems with reasoning, behavior and interaction capabilities with their environments in an intelligent way.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (983, 'en-UK', 'An enterprise architecture attempts to describe and control the structure of an organization, processes, applications and systems in an integrated way. The unambiguous specification of the components and their relationships in an architecture requires a coherent modeling language. Such a language should allow the integrated modeling of various architecture domains and should be analyzed by IT people and people with a business background. In this curricular unit, we present an enterprise modeling language that captures the complexity of the domains of an architecture, their relationships and allows the construction of integrated models. The language provides architects with concrete tools to improve their architectural practices.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (984, 'en-UK', 'This curricular unit explains to students the main concepts, principles and methodologies necessary to manage IS in organizations. The unit also provides the necessary skills in synthesis, written communication, problem solving, critical thinking and practical application of knowledge in areas such as IT governance, Big Data governance, and management methodologies, such as ITIL and COBIT.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (985, 'en-UK', 'This curricular unit aims to provide students with the technical skills for IT security administration. Aspects of communication systems, computer networks, organizational information systems and distributed systems. Understand the set of methods and tools to perform the tasks associated with an IT Security specialist.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (986, 'en-UK', 'The main objectives of the course are the theoretical and practical approach to the theme of IT infrastructure management, including the planning and management of network services that integrate and/or support these infrastructures, support for the operation and maintenance of these infrastructures (planning, monitoring, fault management, service level management, AAA, etc.), protocols for the support of network and IT service management, and the administration of services and IT infrastructures in virtualized and/or cloud-installed environments.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (987, 'en-UK', 'The main objective of the course is the study of methodologies for the modeling and performance evaluation of communication networks. The course covers the fundamentals of probability theory and stochastic processes in the perspective of modeling and performance analysis of communication networks. In addition, the course covers simulation methodologies for performance evaluation of communication systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (988, 'en-UK', 'After completing this curricular unit, students should:\n - be able to describe an architecture accurately;\n - recognize the main architectural styles existing in software systems;\n - propose architectural alternatives for a problem, and choose among them;\n - have the necessary skills to build a medium-sized software system that satisfies an architectural specification;\n - use the correct development tools to accelerate these tasks;\n - understand the formal definition of an architecture and be able to reason about its properties;\n - use domain knowledge to specialize an architecture for a given family of applications.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (989, 'en-UK', 'This curricular unit addresses in depth the areas of software engineering related to verification, validation and certification. The aim is to provide students with comprehensive knowledge about software quality and the technical activities carried out to ensure the quality and reliability of software, including static and dynamic analysis, development models and standards, and software certification.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (990, 'en-UK', 'To present, discuss and develop engineering solutions inspired by nature (i.e., biological, social, physical) for problems of high complexity that either have no analytical solution or are computationally intractable. To learn how to evaluate rigorously, i.e., using statistics, alternative solutions to problems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (991, 'en-UK', 'Pattern Recognition (PR) studies the design, development and implementation of systems capable of recognizing patterns in data. This curricular unit teaches the algorithms that allow the exploration of PR applications, formalizing them, with analytical models widely used in the most diverse domains. Basic concepts, models and tools for the understanding and design of a PR system.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (992, 'en-UK', 'Service engineering provides an important contribution to the definition, design, modeling, execution and analysis of services. The curricular unit presents modeling languages, methods, methodologies, applications and case studies with actionable results, illustrating the techniques that can be used on a large scale using real-world examples to design services.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (993, 'en-UK', 'The Business Process Management curricular unit introduces concepts and approaches for managing and improving business processes. It focuses on understanding, designing and optimizing processes.\n Students will learn to identify, design, document, model, evaluate and improve business processes, becoming aware of the inherent challenges. They will understand how information technology can be used to automate, manage, transform and improve business processes, gaining skills in using some tools. They will understand the challenges, advantages and risks involved in inter-organizational processes and in outsourcing business processes.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (994, 'en-UK', 'This course has as its main objective the study of complex systems, whether they are physical (e.g., the climate), biological (e.g., genetic regulatory networks), cognitive (e.g., the mind) or social (e.g., financial markets). We will focus on the concepts, models and tools necessary to understand these systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (995, 'en-UK', 'In this course, students acquire the knowledge necessary to design and develop ubiquitous systems and to integrate them with existing information systems. Special attention is given to positioning methodologies, place representation and context awareness, privacy and security, and evaluation of ubiquitous systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (996, 'en-UK', 'Concepts of conventional database management systems (DBMS), big data management systems, scalability and performance are addressed. Data management systems in other environments are also addressed. Basic concepts include hardware, physical organization, indexes, search processing and optimization, transactions, backups and recovery, as well as aspects related to application development. In addition to these, the curricular unit will focus on the placement and management of data in parallel, distributed and mobile environments, replication issues, consistency, transactions and availability in these environments. Current topics (which may evolve over the years) are addressed, such as Map-Reduce and Hive, vertical databases, NoSQL systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (997, 'en-UK', 'To understand the aspects related to the geometric and radiometric formation of images. To learn methods to estimate elements in the image and relate them to 3D structures. To learn methods for 3D reconstruction and 3D motion estimation.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (998, 'en-UK', 'This course aims to study the main methodologies for developing Business Intelligence solutions and to show how Data Warehouses(DW), OLAP and Data Mining(DM) techniques can be combined to build information systems to support decision making.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (999, 'en-UK', 'The nature of the activity of a computer engineer is so unique that it requires knowledge of project management techniques, namely in terms of resource management, both human and computational, risk analysis, planning, monitoring, etc. This course aims to address the main project management techniques as an engineering activity, i.e. with finite costs and deadlines, including aspects of personal and organizational relationships, as a result of the need to work within teams of reasonable size (8 to 12 people), in real projects with real clients.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1000, 'en-UK', 'The main objectives of the internship are the following:\n - Software and information and communication systems project and development techniques\n - Conducting technological development projects\n - Contact with project development in a business environment\n - Initiation to basic and applied research activities\n - Integration into the labor market\n - Preparation of a document with the internship/dissertation proposal including the following aspects:\n - State of the art analysis\n - Justified choice of tools and methodologies to be used\n - Requirements analysis for the topic to be developed\n - High-level specification of the system to be developed / work to be carried out including specific objectives and schedule for the second semester.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1001, 'en-UK', 'To provide in a systematic way the technologies and foundations for the integration and development of information and decision support systems in clinical applications. In particular, the aim is to present the most significant protocols and approaches in clinical information systems, the architectures and technologies used for the construction of tele-medical systems (namely pHealth systems), and also algorithms for the analysis of clinical information to support diagnosis.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1002, 'en-UK', 'It is intended to provide (in-depth) knowledge in Robotics for the acquisition of skills to all:\n 1. those who intend to operate and/or develop applications that use robots or robotic systems;\n 2. those who intend to develop/design robotic systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1003, 'en-UK', 'The objectives of the course are the knowledge of fundamentals of telematic applications, applications for the Internet and emerging services on the Internet. The paradigms, technologies and protocols for supporting multimedia applications on the Internet will also be addressed. Students should develop critical analysis and presentation skills of current solutions and future challenges in the areas of telematic applications.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1004, 'en-UK', 'The central objectives of the course are the theoretical and practical approach to the theme of management of services and high-performance computer infrastructures, including the planning and administration of these infrastructures (specification and design of data centers, operations and maintenance, resource management, energy efficiency aspects), the planning and administration of these services and the communications that support them (resilience, quality of service, management of service level agreements, energy efficiency).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1005, 'en-UK', 'The main objective of the Semantic Web course is for students to acquire a set of skills: - Ability to build and manage ontologies\n - Ability to represent an ontology in a Semantic Web language (RDF, RDFa, RDFs and OWL)\n - Ability to use triple stores, SPARQL, Semantic Search and reasoning mechanisms\n - Ability to apply and use ontologies represented through Semantic Web languages, in applications for the Internet or Intranets\n - Ability to specify, design and develop systems/applications for the Semantic Web\n - Ability to reuse ontologies available on the Internet');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1006, 'en-UK', 'Basic training in Linear Algebra. Mastery of the following subjects: vector spaces, linear transformations, Euclidean spaces, eigenvalues and eigenvectors.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1007, 'en-UK', 'Basic training in Mathematical Analysis. Mastery of the following subjects: sequences, differential and integral calculus of real functions of one real variable. Introduction to numerical series.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1008, 'en-UK', 'To provide knowledge about fundamental concepts related to the programming activity, namely, algorithm, procedural abstraction and data abstraction, programming as a construction of abstractions, programming paradigms. After attending the course, students should master the concepts presented and be able to develop programs in a high-level programming language, Python.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1009, 'en-UK', 'Students should master the basic concepts and the general operation of a computer, the material structure that allows the execution of programs. They should be able to describe the operation of the basic elements, processor, memory system and input and output system, and their interaction. In particular, they should be able to understand the internal structure of a processor and the process of executing instructions.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1010, 'en-UK', 'The main objective of this course is to give students an overview of computer engineering in society, companies, innovation and research.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1011, 'en-UK', 'This course provides students with the mastery of differential and integral calculus of functions of more than one real variable, including the fundamental theorems of calculus. Applications to Physics.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1012, 'en-UK', 'To gain programming knowledge in an imperative language. To acquire knowledge about basic sorting and searching algorithms. To be able to select, create and use elementary data structures. To be able to design iterative and recursive algorithms, for problem solving. To be able to analyze the complexity of the algorithms used to solve a given problem in order to choose the most efficient ones.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1013, 'en-UK', 'The aim of this course is for students to have knowledge about the components of a logic, to be able to develop proofs in the deductive system, to be able to use the semantic formalism, to be able to relate the deductive system and the semantic system and to prove properties about these relations. They should acquire notions about automatic reasoning and be able to develop programs using the logic programming paradigm.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1014, 'en-UK', 'To develop rigorous mathematical reasoning. To master the mathematical concepts and tools necessary for the analysis of procedures and algorithms, both in terms of their correctness and efficiency.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1015, 'en-UK', 'Basic training in: functions of a complex variable, ordinary differential equations, Fourier analysis methods applied to the solution of partial differential equations.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1016, 'en-UK', 'The aim is to provide students with the introduction to the fundamental professional skills necessary for the functioning of organizations such as: Microeconomic Framework, Strategic Management, Marketing, Human Resources Management, Accounting and Project Evaluation.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1017, 'en-UK', 'This course presents the basic concepts and principles of classical mechanics, wave phenomena, and special relativity, reinforcing the understanding of these concepts through applications to the real world. Students should be able to manipulate these concepts and apply them to problem solving. Students will be motivated by examples of applying physics principles in other areas of scientific and technological knowledge.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1018, 'en-UK', 'To know: the object-oriented programming paradigm, its advantages, disadvantages and limitations; the design patterns paradigm, both in development and in application refactoring. Skills to be acquired: mastery of the object-oriented programming paradigm, namely the concepts of encapsulation, abstraction, inheritance and polymorphism; ability to use an object-based programming language; ability to use design patterns; and mastery of writing evaluation tests.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1019, 'en-UK', 'To know the fundamental concepts underlying operating systems, with emphasis on their mechanisms and algorithms, as well as the internal structure of the most relevant operating systems. To program, at the system level, using all the functionalities of the operating systems taking into account the sequential and concurrent programming models.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1020, 'en-UK', 'Intermediate level training in algorithms and complexity, familiarizing students with techniques for analyzing and synthesizing algorithms and data structures. Knowledge of the fundamentals of algorithm analysis and synthesis. Analysis of the practical implementation of algorithms and data structures. Comprehensive perspective of the applications of algorithms in Computer Engineering.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1021, 'en-UK', 'This course presents the basic concepts and principles of electromagnetism and physical optics, reinforcing the understanding of these concepts through applications to the real world. Students should be able to manipulate these concepts and apply them to problem solving. Students will be motivated by examples of applying physics principles in other areas of scientific and technological knowledge.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1022, 'en-UK', 'To learn the fundamental principles and rules for the design and development of usable User Interfaces. To identify users and the tasks they want to perform with the interactive system being developed. To be able to evaluate interfaces at different stages of their development, applying the most appropriate evaluation techniques. To identify critical factors in interface design. To understand and make compromises between the various constraints that interface design is subject to. To frame interface design within the computer engineering project.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1023, 'en-UK', 'Introduction to the study of probability theory and statistical inference, with a view to understanding and applying its main concepts and methods.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1024, 'en-UK', 'To understand and be able to use the concepts of Turing machine, computation and computational resource. To understand and deepen the concepts of algorithmic "task" and non-algorithmic "task". To know the limits for algorithmic "tasks". To understand computation as a physical-mathematical concept and not as a purely mathematical concept. To experiment with concepts and techniques in interactive computational environments.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1025, 'en-UK', 'The course introduces the design and analysis of databases. The course focuses on the relational model, covering the logical design of databases (schema design) and its implementation, as well as transaction management systems. Some aspects of parallel and distributed database systems, unstructured and semi-structured information management will also be addressed. The course aims to expose students to the basic concepts necessary for the design and conception of a database management system, as well as practical issues of its implementation within the scope of a team project.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1026, 'en-UK', 'This curricular unit aims to provide basic knowledge on interactive computer graphics. The fundamentals of the representation and creation of synthetic images from three-dimensional scenes are taught. In this context, students will see master elementary geometric transformations and understand the operation of the 3D visualization pipeline and its main stages. At the end, students will be prepared to design and develop interactive graphical applications.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1027, 'en-UK', 'To introduce the subject of Artificial Intelligence to the student, so that he/she acquires the basic knowledge of this area of computer science and motivates him/her to follow the area of Artificial Intelligence. To serve as a basis for more advanced Artificial Intelligence courses.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1028, 'en-UK', 'Students should acquire a comprehensive and up-to-date view of computer architectures at the level of their various components: processors, memory system and inputs and outputs. Students should also be able to understand the constraints for the evolution of computational systems and to evaluate strategies for program optimization taking into account the underlying computational architecture, based on performance metrics.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1029, 'en-UK', 'To be able to critically analyze the various options taken in the design of computer networks, their architectures and protocols. To know the main Internet protocols. To be able to program network applications using the sockets interface.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1030, 'en-UK', 'To provide students with the fundamental skills for the analysis of engineering problems in which the solution can be conceptualized as a system, using requirements engineering and conceptual model development techniques (especially in UML, SysML and BPMN)');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1031, 'en-UK', 'Acquisition of concepts about the definition of programming languages. Obtaining knowledge about the analysis (front-end) and synthesis (back-end) methods most used by compilers. Lexical and syntactic specification, as well as the semantic analysis of computing languages, with special emphasis on programming languages. Develop a compiler for a simple programming language that generates executable machine code.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1032, 'en-UK', 'To convey to future computer engineers the notion of the enormous social impact that ethical aspects have on the development and use of products and services based on information technologies. To teach the fundamentals necessary for them to make the right choices when faced with concrete situations involving the development, operation and use of information systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1033, 'en-UK', 'To transmit a roadmap for software development, from requirements gathering to program maintenance. To integrate the knowledge acquired in other subjects in the broader context of the development process. To motivate for software development as an engineering, which integrates the technological aspects of computing with the social and human factors of product construction.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1034, 'en-UK', 'To analyze the architectures and technologies that allow the development of distributed applications that can guarantee non-functional requirements such as reconfigurability, security, fault tolerance and scalability. Acquisition of knowledge that allows the development of an application with a distributed architecture. To program distributed applications. To interpret security requirements by formulating policies and implementing secure mechanisms in the application code. Analysis of reliability and availability requirements and introduction of fault tolerance mechanisms.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1035, 'en-UK', 'To train in the methods, techniques and languages of quality software design using software architecture and design pattern approaches. To study the methods and techniques of moving from the problem space to the solution space in order to ensure traceability between system requirements and their design. To read, evaluate and write software architectures.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1036, 'en-UK', 'To learn formal techniques for requirements specification and software development. To understand the importance and learn methods for program correctness verification. Use of automatic tools for program verification.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1037, 'en-UK', 'The learning objectives of Information Systems Project Management are aligned with those of the course “IS 2010.4 IS Project Management” of the curriculum “ACM/AIS IS 2010 Curriculum Guidelines”');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1038, 'en-UK', 'Students should be able to: 1. Understand the differences and similarities between the fundamental components of an IT infrastructure solution 2. Understand how the components of an IT infrastructure should be organized in different organizational environments 3. Understand the principles underlying the virtualization of IT services 4. Configure a small-scale IT infrastructure solution, including servers, data storage, network, security devices and clients 5. Understand the architecture and trade-offs involved in designing and managing an IT infrastructure solution in large-scale organizational environments 6. Understand the role of service management and control environments in managing large-scale IT infrastructures 7. Understand the opportunities that dynamic provisioning infrastructures, such as cloud computing platforms, create for organizations 8. Analyze and evaluate the implications for IT infrastructure design of existing security and business continuity solutions 9. Minimize the impact of IT infrastructure solutions on the environment and resource consumption');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1039, 'en-UK', 'The Business Process Engineering and Technology course aims to introduce concepts, techniques and tools associated with Business Process Management (BPM). Emphasis will be placed on the BPM life cycle and its management in the engineering plan. Topics include identification, documentation, modeling, verification and improvement of an organization''s business processes through analysis, design and process automation techniques.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1040, 'en-UK', 'The learning objectives of Foundations of Information Systems are those of the course “IS 2010.1 Foundations of Information Systems” of the curriculum “ACM/AIS IS 2010 Curriculum Guidelines”: 1.	Provide a sociotechnical approach to organizational information systems; understand how and why information systems are used in organizations today 2.	Explain the relationships between the technology, people and organizational components of business information systems 3.	Know the main technology components of information systems 4.	Understand how companies use information systems to support their activities and create competitive advantages 5.	Understand how information systems enable new forms of trade between individuals, organizations and governments 6.	Know the new technologies that enable new forms of communication, collaboration and partnerships 7.	Understand how information systems enable relationships with customers and suppliers, and how they are used to strengthen organizational structures and business processes 8.	Understand how information systems can support decision making at different levels and functions of organizations 9.	Understand how organizations develop and acquire information technologies and systems 10.	Understand the value of investments in information systems, as well as learn how to prepare a business plan for a new information system, including cost and benefit estimates 11.	Mitigate risks, as well as plan and recover from disasters 12.	Understand how to ensure the security of information systems, considering both technological and human aspects 13.	Assess the ethical issues of information systems, and the impact of information systems on fraud and crime');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1041, 'en-UK', 'To understand the system-level problems underlying the design and development of applications in large-scale networks (e.g. on the Internet). To know the existing solutions in the context of the application support platforms mentioned above with emphasis on architecture, communication models, scalability, performance and security. To specify, design, analyze and implement distributed applications in large-scale networks as well as their respective support platforms for their execution.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1042, 'en-UK', 'The objective of this course is to provide the student with a set of concepts, methodologies and computer security tools that will allow him/her to approach the subject in the face of a wide range of technologies, such as: local networks, personal networks, global networks, secure code development, operating systems, distributed systems and communication protocols.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1043, 'en-UK', 'This course introduces and discusses the state of the art in the design and development of 3D graphics applications, with concerns about real time, interactivity and realism, through the use of the OpenGL and WebGL graphics APIs. It includes the development of an immersive 3D graphics application on a mobile device using a pair of low-cost Virtual Reality glasses, the Google Cardboard. The course also covers the latest advances in GPU technology and its applications to computer simulation and games. After attending this course, students should be able to describe and justify methods, procedures and elementary techniques used in Interactive and Real-Time Virtual Environments systems, identifying the underlying terms, concepts and basic principles.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1044, 'en-UK', 'To learn the guiding principles and methodologies of user-centered design of interactive systems. To learn the need for user knowledge and needs and their involvement in the construction of interactive systems. To adapt this knowledge to user-centered development methodologies. To apply evaluation models according to the project phase. To carry out a project of an interactive system based on the acquired knowledge and with user involvement at several levels.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1045, 'en-UK', 'The objective is to give students the knowledge in the area of data and information visualization that will allow them to design and execute high-impact visualizations as a privileged vehicle for transmitting quantitative and qualitative information. The area of Information Visualization will be introduced, after which a methodology for domain analysis and design of effective visualizations will be taught. Once this is known, the various types of variables (continuous, nominal, ratio, etc.), data encodings (color, position, size, etc.), and visual metaphors (scatter plots, bar charts, heat maps, etc.) will be studied. Students will also be introduced to interactive visualization techniques, and will learn to evaluate the effectiveness of visualizations using appropriate metrics.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1046, 'en-UK', 'To know the basic concepts, main formalisms, techniques and algorithms, knowledge bases and corpora involved in the area of Natural Language Processing. To understand the major tasks involved in processing a sentence, paragraph or text and to understand the difficulties of each of these tasks. To know the main applications of the area and to be able to identify the technology involved. To understand the tasks that are achievable with current technologies.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1047, 'en-UK', 'To deepen the themes of searching for solutions to complex problems and planning actions. To recognize the different types of problems to be solved. To master the main methodologies and search strategies. To understand which methodology and strategy to apply for each type of problem. To be able to solve reasonably complex problems. To understand the specificity of the problem of action planning and why it needs a more powerful approach. To study the fundamentals and approaches of action planning and to be able to solve simple planning problems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1048, 'en-UK', 'To introduce the fundamental concepts of information discovery from large amounts of data. To make students skilled in creating systems capable of discovering hidden information through the application of data mining techniques. To make students skilled in evaluating the discovered information, in particular in comparing the different discovered models.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1049, 'en-UK', 'Logic is one of the pillars of Computer Science (CS), finding application in all areas of CS. Concrete examples include databases, intelligent information systems, artificial intelligence, but also the specification, validation and verification of software, hardware and networks. The objective of this course unit is to provide advanced training in approaches to solving computational problems related to Logic. Students are enabled to analyze, model and solve computationally difficult problems using Logic. Additionally, they are trained in the engineering aspects essential in the construction of software for Logic problems: operation and implementation of a deductive system and algorithmic techniques and data structures fundamental to the implementation of Logic-based tools.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1050, 'en-UK', 'To characterize computational classes, identify complete sets, distinguish uniform from non-uniform complexity and perform reductions; to study open problems in computational complexity.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1051, 'en-UK', 'This course focuses on the study of complex networks, with a focus on algorithms, models and applications for both artificial and real networks, such as social networks, information networks, the Internet, and biological networks. The graphs inherent in these networks share some recurring characteristics: large size; sparse; scale-free; small-world and clustering effect; communities; etc. In this context, we are interested both in the development of scalable algorithms and data structures for an effective analysis of these complex networks, and in the elaboration of theoretical models capable of describing the patterns found empirically. The applications are numerous, ranging from search engines, information diffusion on the internet, social networks, blogs, viral marketing, network tolerance to destructive events, epidemiological phenomena in networks, computational biology, with links to social sciences, physics and economics.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1052, 'en-UK', 'The Data Analysis and Integration course aims to teach students the most important concepts of data integration from two different perspectives: virtual, where data sources can be queried through a mediation architecture; and wharehoused, where a materialized data repository (called a data warehouse) is populated with data from the sources. Additionally, the course will teach the techniques that can be used to explore the information: OLAP and reporting in a wharehoused architecture, and mash-up systems in a virtual architecture.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1053, 'en-UK', 'The Information Processing and Retrieval course aims to provide a complete and up-to-date introduction to the key concepts, technologies, and data processing mechanisms used in the areas of Information Retrieval (IR), Information Filtering (IF), and Information Extraction (IE). Students in the course will learn the fundamental theoretical concepts in these areas, acquiring the theoretical and practical skills necessary to: - Design modern solutions for the processing, management and querying of large volumes of unstructured or semi-structured information. - Automatically classify and group sets of resources (e.g., large sets of text documents) through descriptive features. - Design systems for the retrieval and filtering of relevant information from large collections, based on keywords, examples, or user profiles. - Design systems for extracting information from text documents, or from the Web. - Evaluate comparably different systems for the extraction, filtering and retrieval of relevant information.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1054, 'en-UK', 'To understand the most common software security problems and their root causes. To know guidelines, techniques and tools for their prevention or detection, and the best principles behind these techniques.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1055, 'en-UK', 'The objective of the course is to study the techniques and forensic methodologies applied to digital evidence. During the course, students will learn the different phases of the forensic methodology as well as its application to the collection and processing of digital evidence in different media, namely evidence collected from the network, from the volatile and persistent memory of information systems and active network management systems and also from the memory of mobile devices. Some legal aspects relevant to the process of collecting and processing data will also be addressed in order to allow the production of evidence in court.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1056, 'en-UK', 'Computer graphics for games covers theoretical and practical aspects of the development of graphics engines for video games (game engines). It covers the different subsystems present in a game engine, including, among others, rasterization subsystems, character animation, and physics, and discusses the necessary articulation between the various subsystems to support the development of gameplay. After attending this course, students should understand how a modern graphics engine works and be able to develop their own graphics engines for games.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1057, 'en-UK', 'This course allows the student to acquire skills for designing a game experience and developing prototypes that realize that experience. The skills are developed by fostering discussion about what a game is, what its constituents are and the relationship of the game to its players (taking into account their differences). The student develops his work based on design documents and prototype construction.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1058, 'en-UK', 'To recognize the differences between traditional AI and the application of AI techniques to the development of Computer Games, where other factors such as gameplay are more important than the intelligence of the opponent. To know the practical problems of AI development for Computer Games, as well as the different aspects of the techniques applied in commercial Computer Games. To know how to design and build an AI system for a computer game, whatever its style: action, sports, strategy, narrative, etc.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1059, 'en-UK', 'Bioinformatics develops computational methods and algorithms for the processing of biological data and uses mathematical and statistical modeling to define testable hypotheses about biological entities and processes. This introductory course aims to familiarize students with the computational and mathematical methodologies that underlie many of the approaches that support new developments in this area. Additionally, it aims to develop critical thinking through the reading and analysis of scientific publications relevant to the discipline. The practical component of the course aims to provide students with the ability to develop software tools for the processing and integration of biological and clinical data.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1060, 'en-UK', 'To provide students with knowledge about embedded systems and real-time systems with emphasis on the design, development and testing of applications. To address the specificity of embedded systems in terms of hardware architectures, buses, communication networks and cyber-physical interfaces. To study software architectures, multitasking operating systems and real-time scheduling policies. To analyze ways of optimizing programs in order to improve the performance, consumption and cost of systems. To introduce methodologies for system design and requirements analysis. Case studies and application domains: identification and access to services based on electronic media (smart cards) and biometrics, sensors in personal devices (smartphones).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1061, 'en-UK', 'To provide students with the skills to: Design medium-complexity digital electronic systems in a structured way. Understand and apply the fundamental synthesis and optimization techniques at the architectural level. Simulate and synthesize digital systems using hardware description languages. Understand and use the features of computer-aided design tools. Implement digital systems using programmable logic devices (FPGAs and PLDs).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1062, 'en-UK', 'To provide a modern perspective on high-level systems control, especially control and decision based on intelligent techniques (soft computing). To provide students with knowledge of the theory, design and application of soft computing techniques, with special emphasis on fuzzy systems, neural networks, and genetic and biological agent-inspired optimization algorithms. The techniques used should be applied synergistically in modeling, control, classification, decision and optimization problems in complex large-scale systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1063, 'en-UK', 'This course introduces methods of image analysis and perception of the world through cameras. The course includes: filtering, segmentation, object recognition, detection and tracking, camera self-localization, 3D scene reconstruction.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1064, 'en-UK', 'To develop artificial intelligence mechanisms in robots that provide robotic platforms with the ability to interact with humans in a social way. To be able to integrate and evaluate aspects such as intentionality, credibility, emotions and collaboration in human-robot interaction.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1065, 'en-UK', 'The fundamental concepts involved in systems composed of several physical agents with different degrees of autonomy (sensors, processors, actuators, robots) distributed spatially are addressed. Methods of mapping and map representation are described. The fundamental concepts and methods of self-localization in the presence of uncertainties in observation and motion model are introduced. Methods for integrating information from multiple sensors for positioning and representing the map of the world where the sensors are located are presented, as well as methods for solving problems in cooperative systems, including cooperative perception and task assignment, planning and coordination. The course ends with an integrative perspective of the various modules taught.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1066, 'en-UK', 'To master advanced programming techniques and the most suitable problems for their application. To understand the limitations of current programming languages and to know how to overcome these limitations. To be able to anticipate the impact of using advanced techniques on the operation, ease of development and ease of maintenance of a program. To understand the reflection capability of programming languages in the introspection and intercession aspects and at compile, load and execution times. To understand the difference between programming and meta-programming and the usefulness of code models. To understand meta-classes, meta-object protocols, and their intercession capabilities. To understand aspect-oriented programming and its application to cross-cutting requirements. To understand linguistic abstraction, evaluators, and meta-circular evaluators. To be able to provide evaluators with meta-programming, delayed evaluation, and non-deterministic evaluation mechanisms.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1067, 'en-UK', 'The size and complexity of software programs has been growing, so it is becoming increasingly important to be able to validate the correctness of programs. One of the main costs in software development is its validation. There are several validation techniques, with software testing being one of the most widely used techniques. The Software Testing and Validation (STV) course provides advanced training in software testing techniques, including manual, semi-automatic and automatic techniques. The STV course also provides training on additional software validation techniques, including static analysis and model checking. The course also provides contact with academic and industrial software validation tools.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1068, 'en-UK', '1. Understand the enterprise engineering lifecycle, including governance and organizational transformation processes. 2. Understand the fundamental theories underlying enterprise engineering. 3. Understand and apply the principles of enterprise architecture. 4. Understand and use enterprise architecture modeling languages, including ArchiMate and DEMO. 5. Understand and use industry-specific organization models and frameworks. 6. Understand and apply business alignment techniques. 7. Analyze case studies of real organizations.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1069, 'en-UK', 'The learning objectives are aligned with: 1. Understanding the various functions and activities in the information systems (IS) area, including the role of IT management and the IS director, the structure of IS management within an organization, and the management of IS professionals. 2. Seeing an organization from a senior management perspective to decide how IS should support core, support, and customer and supplier management processes. 3. Understanding the concepts of information economics at the organizational level. 4. Understanding how IS represents an important source of competitive advantage for organizations. 5. Structuring IS-related activities to maximize the value of IS inside and outside organizations. 6. Understanding existing and emerging information technologies, IS functions, and their impact on organizational operations. 7. Assessing the issues and challenges associated with incorporating IS into an organization. 8. Understanding how strategic decisions are made about IS acquisition, including the ability to evaluate different sourcing options. 9. Applying information to the needs of different industries and areas. 10. Understanding the role of control and IT service management frameworks from the perspective of IS management in an organization.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1070, 'en-UK', 'The Data Administration in Information Systems course aims to provide students with the skills necessary to effectively manage, optimize and use modern systems for managing large volumes of data. Students should be able to: 1. Understand the internal mechanisms of a relational Database Management System (DBMS), including storage management, indexing, query processing and optimization, transaction management, concurrency control, and recovery management. 2. Understand the tasks involved in database administration. 3. Optimize information access in databases that store large amounts of data. 4. Acquire basic knowledge about the various parallel and distributed database architectures, including conventional (SQL) and non-conventional (NoSQL) systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1071, 'en-UK', 'To have an integrative perspective of cloud computing and virtualization, and their conjugation and synthesis, in the design of modern systems in large-scale distributed computing, with their underlying technologies, mechanisms and algorithms. To understand a vertical approach to the various virtualization and cloud computing technologies that offer applications and services greater flexibility, better resource utilization and economic efficiency, and greater scalability and adaptability. To be able to develop scalable and reliable applications and systems for cloud computing, on the adopted virtualization infrastructures and platforms, and application models. To be able to evaluate choices, solutions, and trade-offs involved in the development, use and management of virtualization infrastructures for cloud computing.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1072, 'en-UK', 'The Enterprise Systems Integration course aims to provide a comprehensive overview of integration concepts, methodologies and technologies, from application and service integration to inter-organizational process integration. The course is positioned at the critical interface between technological infrastructures and business processes, aiming to understand the connection and dependencies between them. It will also provide a vision of how to develop a distributed and integrated application infrastructure.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1073, 'en-UK', 'To understand the challenges and problems underlying the design and development of support software (middleware and operating system) for applications in environments with mobile and ubiquitous entities (people, hardware, software). To specify, design, analyze and implement systems (mobile/ubiquitous middleware and operating system) to support the mobility/ubiquity of hardware and software and their users.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1074, 'en-UK', 'To provide an integrated perspective of the aspects of trust in the functioning in the broad sense, covering not only accidental failures, but also malicious failures and intrusions, combining the facets of fault tolerance and security in the development of systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1075, 'en-UK', 'The objective is to give students the knowledge and skills necessary for the effective communication of concepts, trends and information based on interactive graphic applications. The specificities of the various types of data that can be used to communicate will be described, and the best way to use and combine them for this purpose. Subsequently, techniques for extracting metadata and relevant descriptors from the various media, with emphasis on images, will be taught, thus allowing their more efficient manipulation and use. The indexing and retrieval of media based on these metadata and descriptors will be the next object of study. Once the data is in a format that is easy to manipulate, students will acquire skills related to its visual representation, and its exploration in interactive tools. Finally, the issue of how best to present the concepts, trends and information revealed in the interactive application will be addressed with the creation of public multimedia presentations, maximizing their impact and the amount of information transmitted and retained by the audience.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1076, 'en-UK', 'This course introduces and discusses the application of the laws of Physics in the generation of High Fidelity (Photorealistic) 3D images, with special emphasis on the simulation of the physical process of Light Transport and the corresponding interaction with matter. In addition to Ray-Tracing based techniques, the course also includes the development of an interactive 3D graphic application with photorealistic effects, based on the Unity 3D game engine, through the use of its Assets and shaders libraries.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1077, 'en-UK', 'To know the various types of multimedia information and how to manipulate them for the production of content. To recognize the characteristics of a Multimedia Content Production process. To understand the technological constraints that arise in Production, namely in the aspects of capture, coding, processing and visualization of the various media. To know the various types of authoring tools available. To produce Multimedia content; To know the various contexts in which multimedia can be consumed, with emphasis on network aspects (bandwidth requirements, latency, synchronization, etc.) and mobile devices. To introduce some advanced forms of multimedia use such as procedural modeling, generative art and augmented reality. To apply efficient methods of content-based multimedia information retrieval.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1078, 'en-UK', 'To acquire general notions of agents and multi-agent systems; to know how to identify and classify agents and environments, according to different properties. To know how to develop complex systems and from different areas of application, using an agent-oriented methodology. To know how to specify a society of agents to solve a specific problem. To be able to design agents with reactive, deliberative and hybrid architectures. To be able to create societies of agents that communicate, in a practical way, using languages and appropriate platforms.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1079, 'en-UK', 'To recognize the main challenges involved in the development of intelligent systems in scenarios with uncertainty and/or adversarial. To know and apply the main planning and learning techniques in this type of scenario.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1080, 'en-UK', 'To know the various families of advanced knowledge representation and reasoning (beyond Classical First Order Logic). To understand how to represent knowledge in each of these families and the forms of reasoning about it offered by each. To know the advantages, limitations and weaknesses of each of these families both from the point of view of representation and reasoning. To be able to make the appropriate choices of system given a specific problem of representation and reasoning. To be able to build knowledge bases according to each of the families. To be able to represent and solve reasonably complex problems of representation and reasoning. To be able to represent large amounts of knowledge and to be able to share it between several systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1081, 'en-UK', 'To understand the models, techniques, and forms of programming of parallel algorithms. To analyze and design parallel algorithms. To understand the fundamentals of distributed computing.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1082, 'en-UK', 'The objective of this course is therefore advanced training in algorithm development and analysis techniques with particular focus on advanced data structures for indexing and compression, randomized algorithms, approximation algorithms, algorithms for online and real-time processing, and data structures and algorithms distributed and with access to external memory. This course will follow a problem-based learning approach where data structure and algorithm design and analysis techniques will be motivated and explored in an intuitive and constructive way.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1083, 'en-UK', 'Understanding the history and evolution of programming languages and paradigms. Mastery of the fundamental concepts of binding, scope, lifetime, type, control flow, data abstraction, control abstraction, and exceptions. Evaluating the similarities and differences between the various programming languages. Understanding the alternatives in the design and implementation of languages, for example, compiled vs interpreted execution, lexical vs dynamic scope, static vs dynamic typing, reference model vs value model, manually vs automatically managed memory, etc. Understanding the differences between the imperative, functional, logical and object-oriented paradigms.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1084, 'en-UK', 'To know the cryptographic systems and protocols in use, to develop protocols for solving specific problems and to look ahead to future developments.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1085, 'en-UK', 'To give students an overview of the different methodologies and technologies involved in video game development by discussing the main issues of each one. To provide students with tools and techniques to develop video game interfaces with special attention to the control modes used. To provide students with the ability to reflect on the gameplay and the player experience following a conceptual modeling perspective together with an empirical perspective of testing with players. To highlight processes of exploring the experience from the player''s perspective.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1086, 'en-UK', 'It is intended that students master the basic principles and techniques of speech coding, synthesis and recognition.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1087, 'en-UK', 'The overall objective of the course is to provide students with the fundamental principles and concepts related to the use of information technologies in health. Students will acquire essential skills and become familiar with the potential of using information technologies in biomedical research and the crucial role they play today in the various aspects of healthcare delivery.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1088, 'en-UK', 'They will understand the concept of “Intelligent Environment” and will be aware of the multiple areas in which it can be applied; they will recognize the importance of having sensitive and reactive environments that react adequately to the presence of people and their preferences; they will have been introduced to different technologies that can be applied in this domain and will be aware of the main challenges that arise in relation to energy consumption, communication, security, reliability, interface with sensors and actuators and interaction with people; they will have acquired knowledge about three specific application areas: smart homes/domotics and intelligent buildings, wireless sensor and actuator networks, and intelligent mobility systems; they will learn about different energy management strategies in the field of home and building automation, with emphasis on user requirements and preferences; they will be able to define the requirements and address the implementation of a system that monitors an environment and reacts to different events, in accordance with the profile of the people present.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1089, 'en-UK', 'The main objective of the Advanced Computer Architectures course is to create skills to analyze and develop computer systems. The analysis involves modern general-purpose processors with superscalar structures, and hierarchical memory systems with support for virtual memory managed by operating systems. In the development component, the objective of the course is to provide design and testing tools for RISC processors associated with memory systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1090, 'en-UK', 'To understand the concepts and techniques of system-level design of embedded systems with hardware and software components. To model, simulate and synthesize digital systems using system-level methods and tools. To describe examples of applications and systems developed using a co-design approach. To design and implement medium-complexity hardware/software systems using FPGAs.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1091, 'en-UK', 'The main objective of this course is to provide students with the main concepts and fundamental tools for discrete-time signal processing. The Digital Signal Processing course has a strong practical component, presenting illustrative examples of theoretical concepts and their application in real situations.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1092, 'en-UK', 'To analyze, specify, design and implement sensor and actuator networks in their fundamental aspects: Transduction, Computation and Communications.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1093, 'en-UK', 'To introduce the fundamental concepts of manipulator robots and mobile robots: kinematics, dynamics, differential kinematics, path and trajectory planning, control. Presentation of various types of sensors useful in robotics, their operating principle and observation model. Notions of formation control. Programming languages and robot operating interfaces.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1094, 'en-UK', 'Introduction of the fundamental concepts related to advanced robotics in industrial environments, incorporated in production systems, through a theoretical and laboratory combination. The theoretical concepts provided are applied to a Flexible Manufacturing Cell. The aim is to study methods of modeling and analysis of production robotic systems, simulation techniques for this type of system and task planning methodologies (operations), as well as resource and task allocation');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1095, 'en-UK', 'Development of an integrative project work in the area of computer engineering.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1096, 'en-UK', 'To develop in students behavioral skills of teamwork, oral and written expression, languages and international experiences and experience of the reality of companies and the world of work, through the practice of extracurricular activities.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1097, 'en-UK', 'To develop in students behavioral skills of teamwork, oral and written expression, languages and international experiences and experience of the reality of companies and the world of work, through the practice of extracurricular activities.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1098, 'en-UK', 'Writing a Master''s thesis in the area of Computer Engineering');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1099, 'en-UK', 'In this curricular unit common to several engineering courses, some topics of linear algebra and analytical geometry are taught that provide the conceptual theoretical framework and the calculation tools necessary for the understanding and development of various and important applications of mathematics to other sciences and engineering. Among the fundamental skills to be developed by students are the ability to perform formal algebraic calculations and to formulate and solve explicit algebraic problems, including questions of analytical geometry; the ability to use vector and matrix techniques in various applications; the solution of problems using subspaces and linear transformations; the identification and algebraic manipulation of conics and quadrics.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1100, 'en-UK', 'The Elements of Physics course covers various physical phenomena and concepts that are indispensable for understanding modern scientific and technological progress, placing Physics in the context of other Sciences and Engineering. Special emphasis will be given to the developments of the 20th century, presenting, albeit in a qualitative way, the physical models and their limits. On the other hand, it is intended to develop skills in the field of experimentation and critical reasoning ability.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1101, 'en-UK', 'Acquisition of knowledge and skills in calculus with one variable including the study of functions of one variable and integration.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1102, 'en-UK', 'This curricular unit aims to provide the first notions of using web tools and programming. Particular emphasis will be given to the creation of pages, both in standalone mode and through their integration into tools, and to client-side programming. At the end of the curricular unit, students should be able to develop small and medium complexity web pages that model concrete situations and provide answers to the questions raised by them. Students will learn to design programs that manipulate both web interface objects and data structures.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1103, 'en-UK', 'The aim is to provide students with the ability to solve small and medium-sized problems using a multi-paradigm programming language (Python)');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1104, 'en-UK', 'The objective of the curricular unit is to provide a general understanding of the concepts of object-oriented analysis, software development methodologies, and the UML language for building models.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1105, 'en-UK', 'To extend the training in calculus in one variable to the study of series and differential equations. Study of the extremes of functions of several variables.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1106, 'en-UK', 'Training in discrete mathematics that allows for the understanding of mathematical models of a combinatorial nature, very common in computing, telecommunications, the processor industry, the design of integrated circuits, cryptography and security in the transmission of communications, traffic systems, etc.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1107, 'en-UK', 'To know the forms of information representation in digital computers, with emphasis on the representation of numerical information and basic arithmetic operations.\n - To know the logical operations and the electronic components that perform them.\n - To understand the operation of systems with memory and the operation of the main information storage devices\n - To understand the internal organization of digital computers\n - To understand the mechanisms of communication between the computer and the outside world\n - To acquire familiarity with the architecture of processors through assembly programming.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1108, 'en-UK', 'This course is an introduction to object-oriented programming (OOP), using the Java language. The objective is to cover topics such as encapsulation, inheritance, polymorphism, data structures, so that students are able to decompose and build a solution according to OOP principles.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1109, 'en-UK', 'At the end of this curricular unit, students should be able to:\n - Develop fundamental algorithmic strategies involving iteration and recursion\n - Know how to analyze the performance of iterative and recursive algorithms in terms of their algorithmic complexity\n - Know how to apply systematic debugging strategies, failure management and implementation of algorithms and data structures with correctness and robustness.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1110, 'en-UK', 'To justify the need for probabilistic modeling in the context of Computer Engineering. To provide the mathematical tools that allow for the characterization of this modeling in its different aspects (probabilities, statistics and stochastic processes). To explore the possibilities of experimentation opened up by the availability of current computational means. To teach the techniques of discrete event simulation.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1111, 'en-UK', 'This curricular unit aims to provide a detailed overview of communication networks, covering the most relevant technologies and services used in access and core networks.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1112, 'en-UK', 'To understand the relevance of multimedia systems. To understand the need for using techniques for the efficient representation of multimedia information. To know the main technologies and standards for the efficient representation and processing of multimedia information. To know the main factors related to the performance of multimedia systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1113, 'en-UK', 'To present the most important concepts about the organization of current operating systems from a functional perspective; To introduce the environment of interaction with the computer system based on command line processing; To present the operating system as an abstraction that provides the application programmer with a virtual machine model based on system calls; To introduce concurrent programming and the main mechanisms of communication and synchronization between processes; To familiarize students with the interaction interface provided by Unix.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1114, 'en-UK', 'The curricular unit addresses language theory, aiming to equip the student with the ability to design and implement syntax-directed translators, with a focus on building compilers. It is intended that the student acquires:\n - Ability to work with regular languages, including the manipulation of computational models used to describe and recognize them, namely regular expressions, finite automata and regular grammars.\n - Ability to work with context-free languages, both in their interpretation and design.\n - Ability to distinguish lexical and syntactic analysis.\n - Ability to design and implement syntax-directed translators, including compilers.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1115, 'en-UK', 'To introduce students to the principles and practice underlying the design of distributed systems, presenting the most important concepts related to their implementation. Different communication and synchronization paradigms are particularly explored. It is specifically intended to promote: the understanding of the main problems involved in the design of distributed systems; the ability to develop simple distributed applications.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1116, 'en-UK', 'This course covers a set of principles and patterns of object-oriented software design. The aim is to consolidate OOP concepts, how to refactor code, and learn to identify and use software patterns.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1117, 'en-UK', 'This is an introductory course to the area of Human-Computer Interaction that has the following specific objectives:\n - to promote the understanding of the importance of the user interface in an interactive system; - to introduce the bibliography of the scientific area of human-computer interaction - to introduce the concepts, techniques and tools for the design, implementation and evaluation of a user interface; - to develop more generic skills such as critical thinking, teamwork and oral and written communication skills.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1118, 'en-UK', 'At the end of this course, students should have knowledge at the level of the fundamental concepts, methods and techniques in the field of databases, which will allow them to:\n Build a relational data model that is adequate to the requirements of an information system, using the techniques of conceptual and logical design of a database;\n Explore the potential of a database management system (DBMS), including the specification of the database structure with SQL DDL, the manipulation of data with SQL DML, the SQL programming facilities (stored procedures, triggers and functions) and the security mechanisms;\n Understand the different possibilities of interaction with a database and develop applications for data access;\n Understand the role of databases in the general context of the modeling and development cycle of a software system.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1119, 'en-UK', 'This course aims to provide an overview of the area of Information Security, with particular emphasis on the security problems that arise at the organizational level. These will be highlighted in terms of information security and infrastructure security (machines and networks). This course will focus on the basic aspects of information security, the definition of security policies and their implementation using various security mechanisms. In addition, ethical, legal and social issues of security in organizations will be addressed.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1120, 'en-UK', 'To consolidate the fundamental knowledge of current network systems and simultaneously provide students with skills in network planning, monitoring and management.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1121, 'en-UK', 'The overall objective of this curricular unit is to provide students with the fundamental concepts of management in its various functions so that they are able to know, interpret and apply them. It aims to raise students'' awareness of the importance of the business model in the value creation process and to promote familiarity with the methodologies and tools to support the implementation of business ideas.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1122, 'en-UK', 'While the Database course focuses only on the representation and management of structured data using the relational model, this curricular unit covers NoSQL databases, NewSQL databases, distributed databases and distributed processing. Additionally, the issue of access control is also addressed.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1123, 'en-UK', 'The Artificial Intelligence course provides some of the core concepts in the area of Artificial Intelligence, from the notion of agent to search and planning techniques. This course also serves the purpose of familiarizing students with aspects of functional programming, with an emphasis on list processing, recursion and higher-order functions.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1124, 'en-UK', 'To develop a software system in a team, using enterprise-class frameworks. To cement these objectives, students will take on various roles inherent in a development team and build a system throughout the semester using a reference architecture/platform (e.g. J2EE, .NET, Android), integrating external services (e.g. google, sapo).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1125, 'en-UK', 'To introduce the role of Operations Research (OR) in decision making and to present some of the most widely used techniques, namely:\n- to provide a scientific and structured approach to decision making, for solving complex problems in the operations (activities) of an organization, usually in a situation of scarce resources;\n- to represent real-world systems, using mathematical models and algorithms in an optimization perspective;\n- to serve as a social process, in which actors (clients, managers, decision makers and users), researchers and a problem interact, with the main objective of obtaining some support, to improve the quality of the actors'' actions.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1126, 'en-UK', 'The objectives of this curricular unit are: Familiarization with the project methodology in computer engineering, applying and integrating skills developed throughout the 1st cycle of studies.\n- To foster skills inherent in teamwork.\n- To contact real-world problems through seminars given by professionals in the sector.\n- To reinforce documentation, communication and application demonstration skills (prototypes)');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1127, 'en-UK', 'The aim of this course is to provide a general overview of the computer engineering profession and its position in society.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1128, 'en-UK', 'The overall objective of the curricular unit is to provide students with a set of theoretical principles and tools that will allow them to understand and apply a software quality assurance process that is systematic, test-oriented and, as far as possible, automated.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1129, 'en-UK', 'The understanding of the characteristics and operation of different types of algorithms, and the knowledge of possible strategy approaches for certain problems, are fundamental components of computer engineering education. It is intended to provide additional training to that acquired in the 1st cycle (licenciatura) in algorithms, with the main point being to recognize which data structure and standard algorithm are more appropriate to solve a given problem.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1130, 'en-UK', 'In this curricular unit, it is intended that students:\n- Understand the basic concepts of information theory\n- Understand the need for data compression algorithms\n- Get to know and understand the operation of the main data compression algorithms\n- Understand the relationship between data compression, information theory, and its application to data analysis and exploration.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1131, 'en-UK', 'The aim of this course is to study the techniques and algorithms used in text-based information retrieval and extraction (IR and IE). After studying this course, the student should be able to:\n1) understand the fundamental concepts of information retrieval and extraction\n2) implement algorithms and use dictionary-based and machine learning strategies and\n3) evaluate the performance of IR and IE solutions.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1132, 'en-UK', 'The use of Information Visualization methods and tools is an integral part of the development of some types of Information Systems, and is recognized as essential for informed decision making by users.\nThe understanding of the methods and main characteristics of Computer Graphics and Visualization tools are fundamental components of Information Systems training.\nIt is intended to provide basic training in Computer Graphics and Visualization of Data and Information. And use a standard tool: "The Visualization Toolkit".');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1133, 'en-UK', 'This curricular unit focuses on the development of decision support systems using data warehousing and data mining techniques.\nData warehousing refers to a set of database techniques for creating centralized repositories that integrate data from heterogeneous sources. Typically, they store current and historical data, and are used for data analysis, trend analysis, and report creation in decision support systems.\nData mining is an interdisciplinary area oriented to the process of searching for patterns in large volumes of data. These objectives are achieved using pre-processing techniques that aim at normalization and often dimensionality reduction, algorithms that extract relevant information and, finally, the presentation of information in a way that can be interpreted.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1134, 'en-UK', 'This course aims to provide students with the knowledge related to the principles and use of cloud computing, parallel computing and GPU computing. The main objectives are:\n- to learn the fundamentals of various strategies for solving problems that require large-scale computing;\n- to acquire skills to understand the most general concepts related to the Cloud, such as Virtualization;\n- contact with current Cloud computing technologies in order to develop small projects;\n- familiarization with the fundamental concepts of Message Passing and Shared Memory;\n- use of the most used technologies in parallel computing;\n- to acquire skills to understand the programming model and performance improvements that can be obtained through the use of GPUs for general computing and for the development of simple CUDA usage programs.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1135, 'en-UK', 'SA is the culmination of a process of defining a solution that must meet a wide range of technical, operational, quality and cost requirements. It can be analyzed at 2 different levels: distribution and composition. At the distribution level we can have different architectures, including centralized, client-server and distributed. At the composition level we can have different architectures, including component-based and MicroServices-based.\nThe CU addresses some of the most relevant aspects that underlie the definition of a software architecture, both at the distribution level and at the composition level. The objectives defined are the following:\n- To know relevant software architectures both in terms of distribution and composition\n- To know the factors that impact each of the architectures\n- To know how to choose the best architectures to use for a specific case\n- To design architectures for specific cases');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1136, 'en-UK', 'The main objective of this course is to implement a working enterprise-level (J2EE) application developed within a team following a test-based development methodology. Throughout the courses, the main concepts related to testing and software quality will be presented and applied in the projects.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1137, 'en-UK', 'Know the context and operational requirements of computing platforms. Know the main architectures and methods for planning a computing platform. Know the models, mechanisms and tools for resource management in computing platforms. Know the interdependence of systems on a computing platform.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1138, 'en-UK', 'With this curricular unit, it is expected that students will acquire: understanding of the basic concepts associated with computational modeling and simulation; ability to manipulate the tools and methodologies essential for developing simulation projects, from the manipulation of primitive data to the analysis of results; understanding of the phases of the life cycle of a simulation project, from domain analysis and model specification to testing and validation; understanding of the various approaches and simulation techniques; ability to identify problems that can be addressed through simulation and to build the corresponding simulation system; understanding of the basic concepts of formulating optimization problems; knowledge of the types of optimization techniques most suitable for different types of problems; ability to apply practical application of optimizers based on linear programming, integer programming and metaheuristics for solving problems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1139, 'en-UK', '- Acquire a broad vision of the various contexts of use of information systems in organizations: Functional: CRM, ERP, KMS, etc. Operational: front office, back office. Sectoral: areas of use, value chains, actors, etc. - Understand the technologies and basic structures of modern information systems (including virtualization and cloud technologies). - Design and project the basic architecture of an information system and be able to carry out the respective integration and commissioning. - Be sensitive to the ethical, legal and social aspects of information systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1140, 'en-UK', 'Its main objective is to introduce students to the principles and practices underlying the design of distributed systems, presenting the most important concepts related to their implementation. Different communication and synchronization paradigms are particularly explored. It is specifically intended to promote understanding of the main problems involved in the design of distributed systems; ability to develop simple distributed applications; familiarity with the distributed programming environment in Java.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1141, 'en-UK', 'Building on basic knowledge in Artificial Intelligence, typically acquired in the 1st cycle, the Intelligent Systems curricular unit introduces advanced concepts in this area, giving an integrated system-oriented perspective. In particular, it is intended that students become familiar with the basic concepts and know how to use the main techniques in the following areas: Advanced knowledge representation and reasoning techniques; Machine learning; Multi-agent systems');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1142, 'en-UK', 'Curricular unit focused on advanced training in the domains of technologies and knowledge management in Web environments, complementing the training, in the same domains, obtained in the undergraduate degree and in disciplines of the first semester of the master''s degree.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1143, 'en-UK', 'The seminar course aims to familiarize the student with the research and development environment in general, and with the latest advances in the area of specialization, both in R&D and in companies, as well as to address transversal skills in the level of research organization and writing of articles and theses, bibliographic techniques, presentation and communication, ethics and professional deontology, entrepreneurship, etc.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1144, 'en-UK', 'Project management is a well-developed and accepted science in both the professional and academic worlds. Numerous methods, techniques and tools have been developed to cover all aspects of project management, including its evaluation. However, project management and evaluation continues to be a problematic area, i.e. it has not been seen as an organizational process, despite the fact that there is a vision that all organizations would need to carry out projects internally to ensure and/or minimize risk in their main activities, and thus create internal skills to execute their projects. This course aims to provide the theoretical knowledge necessary for project management at the organizational level and the practical knowledge of the tools for planning, evaluation and control of costs, deadlines, material, human and financial resources. The methodology will allow the implementation of a set of good practices for project management and evaluation in its different phases.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1145, 'en-UK', 'To provide a global vision of the fundamental aspects that guide the development of mobile, ubiquitous and pervasive solutions and applications. To present the concepts and technologies that guide the state of the art. Students should be able to understand and discuss protocols and network technologies appropriate for use in ubiquitous and pervasive computing environments. To be able to design and develop ubiquitous and pervasive applications and services.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1146, 'en-UK', 'Quantum Computing is a recent area in rapid development, aiming at the practical component of building quantum computers. In this introductory course, students will be able to acquire the basic mathematical foundations underlying the quantum computing model, along with a global understanding of the most prominent algorithms developed so far and their implications.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1147, 'en-UK', 'The discipline of Visual Computing aims to provide students with fundamental knowledge associated with the algorithms and nuclear operations of the Image Synthesis and Analysis processes, through an appropriate selection of topics from the areas of Computer Graphics and Image Processing.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1148, 'en-UK', 'Objectives for this curricular unit: - To present the historical evolution, theories and process of entrepreneurship in the world and, in particular, entrepreneurship in Portugal; - To provide a set of techniques used to formulate, implement and manage a business idea; - To provide means and ways for the theoretical and practical analysis of the internal and external environments of organizations; - To stimulate the entrepreneurial attitude of the student and in the student; - To encourage the understanding of the process of detecting and analyzing business opportunities; - To provide tools for the analysis of the plausibility and economic and financial viability of a business.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1149, 'en-UK', 'To provide a global vision of the fundamental aspects that guide the development of service architectures in telecommunications. To present software and service development architectures in advanced networks.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1150, 'en-UK', 'The objectives of the curricular unit are: - To provide students with a set of elements that allow them, using a logic of reasoning specific to business sciences, to understand and interpret the functioning of organizations, whether public, private or para-public, from a strategic perspective; - To provide students with a technical and scientific perspective of strategy and competitiveness, both at the planning and implementation levels; - To acquire a basic body of knowledge, in order to allow its application in the business context regarding strategic decision making; - To develop research skills, both bibliographic and field, group work and scientific oral and written presentation. - To recognize the need for continuous adaptation to the environment in which the company operates, namely taking into account the two-way relationship between the company and the environment.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1151, 'en-UK', 'The objective of this course is to develop efficient algorithms and data structures that will be applied to solve optimization problems in terms of elementary geometric objects.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1152, 'en-UK', 'The specific objectives of the curricular unit are the following: - To develop the fundamental elements of quality management in services; - To address different models of service quality assessment; - To deepen the role of the client in defining service requirements; - To discuss project methodologies and definition of service standards; - To detail strategies and tools for the provision of quality services; - To examine the mechanisms for managing service promises.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1153, 'en-UK', 'To study essential concepts related to semi-structured data and complex data types. To study the latest technologies and standards related to this type of data. To apply the concepts studied to real scenarios and use the technologies and standards in the development of computer solutions that facilitate the creation, manipulation, research and recovery within the scope of this type of data and information.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1154, 'en-UK', 'The objectives of this curricular unit are: to study business models and processes, from planning and design to implementation and control, which allow the organization a sustained position in the market; to introduce methodologies and tools that allow to architect and design the business model and to inventory, analyze, represent and automate processes; to study and develop new forms of business implemented using the Internet; to study and develop forms of intra and inter-organizational integration, using perspectives, tools and multidisciplinary skills.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1155, 'en-UK', 'Mastering advanced methods and techniques of concurrent programming in the context of object-oriented programming in Java.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1156, 'en-UK', 'Objectives of the curricular unit and knowledge, skills and competences to be acquired: - Learn the differences between CMS, ERP and CRM. - Understand the different requirements associated with each system, being able to assess the need, validity and feasibility of these in the course of requirements associated with certain business processes. - Learn to analyze integratable components in the various CMSs. - Learn to specify, implement and test integratable components in a CMS.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1157, 'en-UK', 'This is an introductory course to the areas of Virtual and Augmented Reality where it is intended to introduce basic concepts, methods and tools that allow students to design, evaluate and develop simple applications. The main objectives are: - To define and give an overview of the applications of Virtual and Augmented Reality; - To introduce ideas, methods and tools for the design, implementation and evaluation of Virtual and Augmented Reality systems. - It is also intended to promote important general skills, such as critical thinking, teamwork skills and oral and written communication skills.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1158, 'en-UK', 'To introduce the generic concept of PACS; To approach the main modalities of medical imaging from a systemic point of view; To study the main strategies for archiving and transmitting images; To address issues of quality management and control in RIS/PACS environments; To involve students in small development projects related to the PACS/DICOM universe.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1159, 'en-UK', 'The aim of this course is to provide students with a comprehensive education in the field of intelligent mobile robotics, focusing on essential topics in the development of an autonomous and mobile robot.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1160, 'en-UK', 'The general objective of this course is to present and describe the main fundamental concepts of security in computer systems. As many security solutions use cryptographic techniques, this course also provides an introduction to cryptography and cryptanalysis. Security is addressed in various contexts, such as programs, operating systems, virtual machines and databases.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1161, 'en-UK', 'Learn to design and guide the development of a security policy in the organization; Learn to determine appropriate strategies to ensure confidentiality, integrity and availability of information; Learn to apply risk management techniques in order to better manage risks, reduce vulnerabilities, threats and apply appropriate safeguards/controls.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1162, 'en-UK', 'This is an integrating curricular unit where students must demonstrate that they have the skills and knowledge necessary to obtain the Master''s degree in Computer Engineering. The objectives are the following: - To deepen the skills of organization, planning and time management. - To be able to work autonomously, act with initiative and make decisions in order to achieve the objectives defined in the work plan. - To be able to apply technical and methodological knowledge acquired in the course, and to solve problems in new and unfamiliar situations, as well as in enlarged and multidisciplinary contexts. - To be able to present results in a concise, structured and with academic and scientific rigor. - To promote critical thinking and the development of self-criticism.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1163, 'en-UK', 'The student is expected to acquire: - basic knowledge of Linear Algebra; - ability to apply the acquired knowledge in different contexts; - mathematical calculation and reasoning skills in order to build rigorous arguments; - ability to communicate, in writing and orally, in mathematical language; - ability to work in a group; - ability to learn autonomously.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1164, 'en-UK', 'At the end of the semester, students should be able to: - apply results of continuity and differentiability to the study of properties and sketching of graphs of real functions of real variable; - calculate primitives of functions applying the presented techniques; - apply the concept of integral to areas and length of curves. Recognize and calculate improper integrals; - interpret and apply convergence criteria of numerical series; - analyze under what conditions a power series defines a function and establish some of its properties.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1165, 'en-UK', 'Transmission of specific knowledge: propositional calculus, induction in naturals, set theory, binary relations, finite and infinite sets. Contribution to the acquisition of a set of skills: - ability to assimilate information and communicate it; - ability to build rigorous arguments, using mathematical reasoning; - ability of written and oral expression; - ability of independent learning.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1166, 'en-UK', 'At the end of this curricular unit the student should be able to program within the functional paradigm, based on the Haskell language. Namely: - Write programs in Haskell. - Define inductive types and encode recursive functions. - Define algebraic types to model problems, and program with these types. - Understand the notion of principal type and polymorphism. - Use higher-order functions.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1167, 'en-UK', 'The main objective of this curricular unit is to introduce the area of Systems Engineering through its characterization, methodology and representative tools. Within the latter, simulation models, queuing theory and network optimization models are addressed. The learning outcomes are: - Identify systems where simulation models, queuing and optimization can be used to define their configuration or improve their performance. - Obtain and interpret the main performance measures of a Markov queuing system given the arrival and service rates. - Use network models to represent and optimize real problems. - Obtain optimal solutions through the use of software in models referred to in the previous point. - Obtain approximate solutions through the manual application of appropriate algorithms in small-scale network problems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1168, 'en-UK', 'Practical learning of basic programming concepts. Editing/compiling/testing cycle. Programming in the shell of an operating system. Contact with a system for producing quality documentation. Practice in developing software projects in groups.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1169, 'en-UK', 'Upon successful completion of the course unit, each student should be able to demonstrate that they have acquired the following knowledge, skills and abilities:\n - recognize and discuss the organization and architecture of a computer and its evolution;\n - recognize and interpret the main features of the architecture of an instruction set;\n - examine and modify the functionality of imperative programs (C-like), using assembly and machine language;\n - apply and experiment with techniques that impact the performance of code execution;\n - use and analyze program compilation tools, and low-level code analysis and testing (on Unix/Linux);\n - transversal skills, namely the ability to reason in problem solving and the ability to communicate in writing and orally.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1170, 'en-UK', 'At the end of the semester, students should be able to: - interpret the notions of continuity, of directional and global differentiability; - determine and classify free and constrained extrema of real functions of several real variables; - interpret the notion of integrability of a real function over a subset of R^n; - calculate and interpret multiple, line and surface integrals.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1171, 'en-UK', 'To know Einstein''s relativity applying it to concrete problems. To describe mathematically mechanical waves and electromagnetic waves and to apply the concepts of reflection, refraction, polarization, interference and diffraction of electromagnetic radiation. To recognize the corpuscular nature of radiation and the existence of discrete energy levels in matter. To know and apply the different atomic models. To recognize the wave-particle duality for both radiation and particles. To interpret the Heisenberg uncertainty principle and the foundations of Quantum Physics interpreting the Schrodinger equation. To understand the foundations of atomic and molecular structure in the light of Quantum Mechanics. To know the nuclear structure and apply the concepts associated with radioactivity. To understand the harmful effects of ionizing radiation. To acquire basic knowledge about elementary particles and fundamental interactions in nature. To interpret the standard model.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1172, 'en-UK', 'At the end of the semester, the student should be able to: 1) define functions by structural recursion and make proofs by structural induction; 2) manipulate the formal syntax of Propositional Calculus and Predicates of 1st Order of Classical Logic; 3) use formulas of 1st Order Logic to represent sentences in natural language; 4) give meaning to formulas and decide their logical value, in the context of an interpretation; 5) understand and build formal proofs in natural deduction; 6) know some of the consequences of the Theorems of Correctness and Completeness.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1173, 'en-UK', 'At the end of the course, the student should be able to: - solve problems by decomposing them into smaller problems and specifying algorithms for each one; - solve problems involving numerical calculus, string manipulation, file manipulation, information storage and processing of data structures (lists and binary trees).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1174, 'en-UK', 'The knowledge and ability to code algorithms and data structures in an imperative programming language:\n - the ability to generate, execute and test programs coded in C, using a suitable set of utilities\n - the knowledge and ability to analyze the execution of programs on a given architecture, and the skills to develop and apply compliance tests in borderline situations\n - the ability to analyze assembly code and use program debugging tools\n - the skills and abilities to describe, apply and evaluate performance optimization techniques\n - the ability to work in a team and develop algorithms to solve problems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1175, 'en-UK', '1. Describe integration techniques and exemplify applications of ordinary differential equations.\n 2. Qualitatively analyze nonlinear ODE systems.\n 3. Apply computational tools in the context of the curricular unit.\n 4. Describe integration techniques and applications of partial differential equations.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1176, 'en-UK', 'Learning of methodology associated with data collection and analysis in statistics. The objectives expressed in learning outcomes can be described as follows:\n - Summarize and describe data sets.\n - Select a representative sample.\n - Interpret qualitative and quantitative data.\n - Calculate probabilities and determine probability functions.\n - Formulate and test hypotheses.\n - Use specific software (SPSS).');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1177, 'en-UK', 'The main objective of this curricular unit is to provide students with essential knowledge of economics and management that will allow them to make correct decisions in a business environment. The expected learning outcomes are as follows:\n - Understand how an economy works\n - Characterize the general management functions of a company\n - Explain the behaviors of economic agents and their interrelationships in markets\n - Explain the functioning of different market structures\n - Evaluate economic aspects from a decision perspective\n - Acquire basic financial knowledge\n - Apply mathematical and financial knowledge to describe and analyze investment projects.\n - Apply economic analysis tools.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1178, 'en-UK', 'Identify and characterize metrics related to program execution performance and its relationship to high-level language programming\n Identify the impact of the memory hierarchy on the performance of programs written in high-level languages\n Characterize limitations inherent in instruction chaining (dependencies) and design potential solutions\n Analyze and justify the impact of multiple functional units on machine performance\n Describe, apply and evaluate performance optimization techniques\n Identify opportunities for parallel processing exploitation and characterize the limitations inherent in parallel processing');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1179, 'en-UK', 'To define, discuss and relate the basic theoretical concepts related to data communication processes and telecommunications technologies;\n To explain the fundamental components of a digital or analog communication system;\n To understand and relate various concepts from the area of Information Theory in the context of data encoding and communication processes;\n To list and discuss the main limitations of transmission systems;\n To understand the basic multiplexing mechanisms underlying current telecommunications/transmission systems;\n Ability to understand and analyze the frequency domain (spectrum) representation of analog and digital signals;\n To understand the concepts underlying the main algorithms, techniques and tools related to the digitization and processing of multimedia signals;\n To understand the techniques and support theories that allow the detection and correction of errors in digital communications.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1180, 'en-UK', 'The main objective of the Algorithms and Complexity course is to introduce techniques for the design and analysis of algorithms. Learning outcomes:\n 1. Evaluate the correctness of an algorithm\n 2. Determine the asymptotic complexity of an iterative or recursive algorithm.\n 3. Recognize and use fundamental algorithmic strategies.\n 4. Use fundamental data structures (in particular implementations of finite functions and graphs), and use algorithms on them.\n 5. Recognize NP-complete problems and some approximate algorithms for their solution.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1181, 'en-UK', 'In a broad sense, the objective of the curricular unit is to help to have a coherent and integrated vision of how computer systems work: what is, in physical terms, a computer application, what resources it needs, how it interacts with others and with the operating system, which management policies are more appropriate for each type of load and their respective implementation costs, reasons for the system being slow, what actions to take, etc.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1182, 'en-UK', 'Understand the fundamental concepts of OOP (Objects, Classes, Inheritance and Polymorphism;\n - analyze and illustrate the structuring of a domain into classes;\n - build class hierarchies using the notions of abstract class, abstract data type and polymorphism;\n - understand the importance of abstract classes and inheritance in the design of an OOP system;\n - use object-oriented programming languages to build medium-scale, secure, robust and extensible programs.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1183, 'en-UK', '1. Calculate the electric field for discrete and continuous charge distributions.\n Use Gauss''s law to calculate the electric field.\n 2. Apply the concept of electric potential to discrete and continuous charge distributions.\n 3. Understand and use the concept of capacitance and electromotive force\n 4.) Describe the motion of electric charges in the presence of magnetic fields\n 5.) Know the sources of magnetic field. Calculate the magnetic field of some simple systems\n 6.) Know and apply the concept of magnetic induction and inductance.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1184, 'en-UK', 'The UMinho Option will be chosen by students from a set of UCs that will be made available each year at the University level');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1185, 'en-UK', '(i) Program construction: writing functional programs in a compositional way, using algebraic combinators.\n (ii) Program transformation: using program algebra to obtain more efficient programs without compromising their correctness.\n (iii) Program analysis and understanding: using factorization into "fold" + "unfold" pairs (hilomorphisms) as a way to understand the architecture of algorithms and their cataloging.\n (iv) Program synthesis: for-loops from inductive definitions.\n (v) Advanced functional programming: building and reasoning about functional programs with effects in the form of monads.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1186, 'en-UK', 'To know the fundamental principles of Software Engineering, namely modularity, reuse, encapsulation and data abstraction, and to be able to implement them in different implementation languages (C - 1st project and Java 2nd project);\n - To complement experimentally the knowledge acquired in the curricular units of Algorithms and Complexity and Object Oriented Programming;\n - To design and code two medium-sized projects, to be delivered and evaluated in several phases. 1st project C Language Concepts involved: modularity, reuse, graphs, trees, file manipulation. 2nd project Java Language Concepts involved: Java collections manipulation, timing of operations on collections, building user interfaces (MVC pattern), exploring Swing components.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1187, 'en-UK', '1) Distinguish between data, information and knowledge.\n 2) Understand and apply the normal forms and define conceptually the data model for a specific problem.\n 3) Write relational database queries using relational algebra\n 4) Use the SQL language to administer, maintain and query relational databases.\n 5) Develop computer applications that operate on databases, including web-based applications.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1188, 'en-UK', 'Students should be able to:\n - Recognize the different types of UML diagrams ;\n - Understand models (requirements/structural/behavioral) described in UML;\n - Design software systems using UML;\n - Implement software systems from UML models.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1189, 'en-UK', 'Develop the ability to solve problems (deterministic models), with emphasis on systems engineering problems.\n - Know the techniques and methods of Operations Research presented in the Curricular Unit, and be able to apply them in solving instances of small-scale problems.\n - Develop the ability to analyze complex systems, to create models to describe them, to obtain solutions for these models using appropriate computer programs, to validate the obtained models, to interpret the obtained solutions, and to elaborate recommendations for the system under analysis.\n - Understand the importance of solution evaluation, and be able to perform sensitivity analyzes.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1190, 'en-UK' ,'a) To know the characteristics, virtues, limitations and applicability of the shared memory model; b) to know and be able to analyze the various problems arising from programming with concurrent processes; c) to know and be able to apply various types of concurrency control primitives in shared memory systems; d) To know the characteristics, virtues, limitations and applicability of models and architectures of distributed systems; f) to be able to solve classical coordination problems in distributed systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1191, 'en-UK' ,'As a result of learning, students are expected to be able to: - Discuss fundamental concepts about data communication, communication protocols, protocol families and their architecture, including the most common protocol elements; - Analyze and instantiate these concepts, especially at the data link layer; - Have a global and critical view of local computer networks and their operation; - Explain in detail the main functions of the IP protocol; - Be able to implement concrete solutions for setting up an IP local area network, also planning its addressing and routing scheme.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1192, 'en-UK' ,'Understand and use methods for solving equations and nonlinear systems; Solve systems of linear equations by direct methods with partial pivoting; Understand and apply function approximation strategies; Describe and apply numerical integration methods; Understand, choose and use the most appropriate optimization method for a specific problem; Use numerical methods in Computer Engineering problems; Use specific software (MATLAB) to solve problems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1193, 'en-UK' ,'The subjects that are dealt with in the curricular unit come from the area of knowledge that, to a large extent, is situated at the intersection of the scientific areas of Artificial Intelligence, Databases and Computational Logic. (i) The objective of this curricular unit is to introduce students to the paradigms of knowledge representation and logical reasoning, and their application in the design and implementation of intelligent or decision support systems, where the quality of information and the degree of confidence that is placed in the combination of the attributes of a predicate or logical function is crucial. (ii) Understand the relationship between the complexity of a knowledge representation model and the forms of reasoning associated with it and its performance, using this information to define a strategy for its optimization.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1194, 'en-UK' ,'a) To know the techniques and methods of Operational Research presented in the UC, and to be able to apply them in solving instances of small-scale problems. b) To develop the ability to solve problems (stochastic models), with emphasis on systems engineering problems. c) To develop the ability to analyze complex systems, to create models to describe them, to obtain solutions to these models using appropriate computer programs, to validate the models obtained, to interpret the solutions obtained, and to develop recommendations for the system under analysis. d) Understand the importance of solution evaluation, and be able to perform sensitivity analysis.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1195, 'en-UK' ,'Students should develop the following skills by attending this module: - Characterize geometric transformations and references used in computer graphics; - Apply transformations to build complex geometric models and camera positioning; - Local and global illumination algorithms: Gouraud, Phong, Ray-tracing, Radiosity and Virtual Point Lights; - Apply textures and define texture coordinates; - Analyze solutions from a performance perspective using profilers. - Appropriately use geometry elimination solutions, using spatial partitioning. - Apply Analyze algorithms for shadow generation');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1196, 'en-UK' ,'- Describe and apply the different routing algorithms (LS and DV) - Discuss different unicast routing protocols - Plan and implement intra and inter domain interconnection solution - Distinguish the different transport services - Configure security solutions for network and transport layers - Identify, classify and configure basic network services and network management solutions - Describe the operation of the main applications - Classify the different applications according to their QoS requirements');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1197, 'en-UK' ,'Generic Skills: the ability to communicate in writing and orally in the presentation and discussion of the processes used and results obtained; the ability to use generic computer tools in a Linux environment and to prepare documents.'); 
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1198, 'en-UK' ,'- To understand the fundamentals, design and manage the development of a software system. - To analyze and specify in a complete way all the operational and functional requirements of a software system. - To develop, test, document and install software systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1199, 'en-UK' ,'The objective of this curricular unit is to provide students with the skills to understand, use and develop algorithms for processing and analyzing biological sequences, using a programming language for their implementation.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1200, 'en-UK' ,'- To provide students with the basic biological knowledge to understand the problems and tools of Bioinformatics - To promote the knowledge of the main databases and tools available in the area of Bioinformatics - To promote the development of skills in the advanced use of free software repositories in the area of Bioinformatics for the construction of small programs for specific tasks');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1201, 'en-UK' ,'To promote the acquisition of advanced skills in the understanding and implementation of the main algorithms in the area of Bioinformatics, including optimization methods and their use for solving biological problems');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1202, 'en-UK' ,'To promote the acquisition of knowledge and skills in the processes and tools of multivariate data analysis, data mining and machine learning and their applications in Bioinformatics');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1203, 'en-UK' ,'Students should develop the following skills by attending this module: Characterize the graphics pipeline and data flow. Identify the programmable components and their potential; Produce programs running on the GPU to obtain graphical effects or data processing; Design, implement, and evaluate solutions using GPU programming for problems in the area of computer graphics; Analyze local lighting algorithms, and graphical effects from the point of view of their suitability for using GPUs, and final performance. Additionally, it is intended to develop the following transversal competence: Exhibit an adequate written and oral communication capacity, promoting language as a tool for expressing and constructing thoughts, ideas and arguments of their own, based on critical thinking.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1204, 'en-UK' ,'To introduce the state of the art in medical imaging technology, providing an overview of standards, techniques, equipment and applications. To promote the analysis of case studies and simulation of real clinical environments. Skills: Recognize and argue the importance of using computers in the processing of pictorial information in the medical context. Demonstrate knowledge of the concepts associated with imaging systems, image processing, vision and computer modeling in medical imaging. Perform the tasks of developing new functional components using the ImageJ and OsiriX applications.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1205, 'en-UK' ,'Students should develop the following skills by attending this module: Characterize global illumination and describe the various stages of the image synthesis and visualization process; Explain the rendering equation and discuss the meaning of each of its factors; Relate the various global illumination methods to the general model supported by the rendering equation, inferring which illumination phenomena are modeled; Design, implement and evaluate solutions for new illumination problems by recombining known solutions; Recognize the functional and/or performance limitations associated with each global illumination algorithm. Additionally, it is intended to develop the following transversal competence: Exhibit an adequate written and oral communication capacity, promoting language as a tool for expressing and constructing thoughts, ideas and arguments of their own, based on critical thinking.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1206, 'en-UK' ,'This module aims to expose students to advanced techniques in the field of computer graphics by confronting them with practical applications. It is intended that students develop the following skills: Analyze solutions associated with imaging systems, image processing, vision and computer modeling in medical imaging, namely using deep learning techniques; Create image processing applications based on concrete cases, such as traffic sign recognition; Design, implement and evaluate solutions for image generation based on the physics of light transport; Design, implement and evaluate solutions for high-quality real-time image generation using techniques such as Voxelization.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1207, 'en-UK', 'A student who successfully completes the course unit should be able to demonstrate that they have acquired the following skills:\n - characterize and evaluate qualitatively and quantitatively the architecture of parallel/distributed computing systems\n - analyze, measure and evaluate the performance of computing systems in the execution of applications\n - develop and/or modify computational applications in order to optimize their performance and scalability');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1208, 'en-UK' ,'- Learn the theoretical foundations for supporting the analyzed algorithms. - Identify, at different levels (complexity, robustness, efficiency, scalability, etc.) strengths and weaknesses of the analyzed algorithms. - Develop sequential and parallel implementations and discuss the performance and efficiency results obtained with the analyzed algorithms. - Identify, in parallel algorithms, potential load balancing problems and/or high communication costs between computing elements.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1209, 'en-UK' ,'Identify the different types of computing systems, including SMP machines, clusters and grids and discuss their respective advantages and limitations. Analyze and evaluate the hardware and software requirements for planning and installing the equipment. Identify the user requirements necessary to select the software to be installed and maintained. Identify and characterize job management and scheduling policies and evaluate the results of their application. Discuss and evaluate the effective performance of sequential and parallel programs on the platforms studied. Identify the bottlenecks of the runtime environment facing a given computational load. Use the existing tools, at the runtime environment level, to study optimization strategies for shared resources on the different platforms in order to minimize a given cost function (e.g. execution time)');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1210, 'en-UK' ,'A student who successfully completes this course should be able to demonstrate that they have acquired the following skills: - Develop parallel applications capable of running on a wide range of architectures - Implement applications using the most common types of parallel algorithms - Measure and optimize the performance of applications in distributed memory systems - Implement resource management techniques at the application level.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1211, 'en-UK' ,'(Not available)');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1212, 'en-UK' ,'(Not available)');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1213, 'en-UK' ,'(Not available)');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1214, 'en-UK' ,'(Not available)');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1215, 'en-UK' ,'Analyze and understand the main structural and behavioral patterns used for the development of complex and large-scale software systems, taking into account the architectural specificities of multi-layer applications. Be able to develop computational layers that allow controlled and independent evolution of the presentation and data layers and that allow the provision of services as an integration mechanism. Identify the main characteristics of application servers in order to choose the desired programming model and be able to use service-oriented technology as a mechanism for creating parameterizable software architectures.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1216, 'en-UK' ,'Recognize and explain the main performance, reliability and scalability challenges in data management. Know and describe the mechanisms available for query processing and maintaining transactional guarantees. Plan and execute data management solutions, combining, composing and configuring the available mechanisms. Estimate and measure the behavior of data management systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1217, 'en-UK' ,'Understand and explain the trade-offs between cost, performance, and reliability in the design of data centers and their translation into concrete technologies. Apply redundancy, virtualization and centralized administration mechanisms in the development and operation of data centers. Design, plan and implement scalable and high-performance data storage infrastructures. Understand and establish the limits of infrastructures by defining the thresholds for their review and update. Have a global view of infrastructures and the ability to identify their critical points');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1218, 'en-UK' ,'Design user interfaces with usability in mind. Be able to evaluate the designed interfaces using the most appropriate techniques. Understand and explore different techniques for developing interactive layers. Be able to develop presentation layers that allow controlled and independent evolution of the logic and data layers.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1219, 'en-UK', 'To know and understand, based on the RUP, the various stages of the process of designing and developing a complex and large-scale software system and to use the UML language as a basic tool for its modeling;\n - To know and be able to apply advanced software engineering (SE) principles, namely IOC (Inversion of Control), DI (Dependency Injection) and separation of layers (cf. MVC model - model, view and controller), as well as apply usual patterns (“design patterns”);\n - To know how to use Java technologies for web application development, namely Servlets, Java Server Pages (or Java Server Faces or Structs) and Beans (as well as persistence technologies), and use them according to the principles of the MVC model;\n - To be able to model small subsystems of a given software system in Alloy and perform formal verification of the satisfaction of properties that are part of the functional requirements of such subsystems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1220, 'en-UK' ,'Define, within the scope of the entire software engineering process, the intervention of the requirements engineering team and the formal involvement of stakeholders. Choose how the requirements should be captured, in particular decide which techniques to use to gather the requirements from the identified sources. Detect, negotiate and resolve conflicts between the captured requirements. Structure the requirements document at two levels (user requirements and system requirements) and ensure its quality and verifiability. Review the requirements document, ensuring that it describes the intended system, through formal reviews, inspections or prototyping. Manage requirements change, using traceability and impact analysis techniques.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1221, 'en-UK' ,'Design, develop, install and maintain web applications. Identify legal, professional, social and ethical issues involved in the development of usable and accessible web applications. Adapt a web application to other usage contexts, based on the captured requirements. Describe and discuss the techniques, methods and approaches used in web development');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1222, 'en-UK', 'Students who successfully complete this CU should be able to:\n 1. Discuss alternatives for applying PMBoK techniques in software projects;\n 2. Develop a plan for an information systems development project, following the PMBoK guidelines;\n 3. Understand and apply the appropriate methods for recording project progress (Project Execution);\n 4. Apply the techniques proposed by PMBoK to monitor project progress (EVM - Earned Value Management);\n 5. Understand the principles, themes and processes proposed by the PRINCE2 method.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1223, 'en-UK' ,'This course aims to develop students'' skills in the theoretical and experimental aspects of relevant topics in access and core technologies, as well as IPv4 and IPv6 internetworking protocol solutions.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1224, 'en-UK' ,'This course is part of the specialized training component of the course, taught in the 1st year, and is intended to introduce the fundamentals and technologies associated with mobile communications networks. It covers the emission, propagation and reception of radio signals, and introduces the technologies associated with cellular mobile networks and wireless local area networks.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1225, 'en-UK' ,'This course aims to promote the study and knowledge of current and emerging solutions that enable the integration of Applications and Services with different Quality of Service (QoS) requirements on the Internet.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1226, 'en-UK' ,'Understand the principles, techniques and algorithms used for representation, compression, retrieval and processing of multimedia content; Know and differentiate the different technologies and systems and multimedia applications in the network. It also aims to complement the training in Information and Communication Technology with advanced skills in the design, implementation and evaluation of computer solutions for systems characterized by the high mobility of their users and the ubiquity of computing and communication services.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1227, 'en-UK' ,'The objective of this course is to introduce database systems, particularly with regard to their administration and exploitation.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1228, 'en-UK' ,'The objective of this course is to introduce data analysis and its application in the design and implementation of business intelligence or decision support systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1229, 'en-UK' ,'The objective of this course is to introduce the concept of semantic interoperability. The following learning outcomes are intended to be achieved: Identify, describe and define the main concepts related to semantic interoperability. Understand and identify the levels of interoperability and the international standards associated with this thematic area. Understand and identify communication protocols and formats. Study, implement and evaluate archetypes, terminologies and ontologies. Develop software tools for the synchronization and semantic integration of data.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1230, 'en-UK' ,'The objective of this course is to introduce the concept of knowledge discovery. The following learning outcomes are intended to be achieved: Identify, describe and define the main concepts related to knowledge discovery. Select the appropriate methodologies and apply the most recommended available software to solve real-world knowledge discovery problems. Introduce the concept of computer vision. Analyze the results of knowledge discovery tools. Know and be able to implement and evaluate scenarios.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1231, 'en-UK' ,'This course aims to introduce a generic training in the area of network and computer communications systems management. Addressing imminently practical topics, despite the intention to guarantee an important training component on the main theoretical concepts defined in current standards, the theoretical classes are complemented, in the practical part, with small development or research projects, individual or in small groups, which serve to experiment with the most important tools in this domain and which help students to understand and solve the most common problems of computer network management, services, communication systems or distributed applications.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1232, 'en-UK' ,'The skills to be acquired are as follows: Recognize the importance of a security culture in the use of computer networks. Know the technical aspects of computer networks that most expose them to security risks. Recognize the main threats and the typical way in which attacks are carried out. Analyze vulnerabilities in networked systems. Implement and control continuous management processes defined in the context of a computer network security policy. Discuss the evolution of the Information Systems Security phenomenon, not only in the aspect of security technologies, but also of threats.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1233, 'en-UK' ,'Explore and understand the definitions, protocols and standards for Software Defined Networks (SDN). Understand the operation and interconnection of the components that are necessary to build networks that use software for bi-directional communication between applications and the underlying network infrastructure. It will also be necessary to understand various use cases of SDNs, namely scaling and manipulation of bandwidth, incoming traffic and triggered actions, as well as interesting cases around big data, overlay networks in data centers and network function virtualization (NFVs). It is necessary to assess how companies and service providers are taking advantage of SDNs and NFVs to concretize and evolve their services and businesses.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1234, 'en-UK' ,'In this course the objective is to make contact with emerging network architectures. It begins by identifying the main weaknesses of the current Internet architecture, addressing new architectures that better address these weaknesses. For the difficulties in dealing with mobility, Ad-Hoc networks, Vehicular networks and delay-tolerant networks emerge. For performance-related issues, new content-centric architectures (CDN, Peer-to-Peer and NDN). The last item addresses the scalability issues raised by the Internet of Things.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1235, 'en-UK' ,'Abstract the details of a software component in order to obtain a model suitable for formal verification; Model the state of a software component using the unifying concept of mathematical relation; Specify invariants and pre- and post-conditions of operations using relational logic; Specify reactive systems using temporal logic; Use automatic verification tools to establish the validity of a software property.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1236, 'en-UK' ,'(Not available)');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1237, 'en-UK' ,'This Course Unit, which is an integral part of the profile in Formal Methods in Software Engineering, aims to provide training in Software Architecture from a formal perspective and with an emphasis on reactive systems.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1238, 'en-UK' ,'Explain the operation of the most important techniques in software verification. Specify the behavior of programs through contracts. Use tools to verify programs annotated with contracts. Explain the different approaches that have been used to mitigate the state space explosion problem in model checking. Use a symbolic model checking tool. Use automatic software verification tools based on model checking.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1239, 'en-UK' ,'At the end, students should have: the ability to develop specifications of the syntax/semantics of languages and problems in general with grammars; the ability to generate programs (prototypes) using automatic tools based on grammars; the ability to build powerful front-ends for the analysis of programming languages; the ability to design and implement complex data structures for intermediate representation of the information extracted from the code analysis; the ability to create visual representations suitable for the clear understanding of the complex knowledge held; the ability to develop software as a task of transforming programs and/or specifications into efficient implementations; the ability to use program transformation techniques to optimize programs (e.g. partial calculation, dead code detection), debug programs and improve the structure of programs; the ability to develop tools for code comprehension.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1240, 'en-UK' ,'At the end, students should be able to: formally specify knowledge using various methodologies: taxonomies, thesauri and ontologies; add descriptive semantics to digital objects; specify taxonomies in SKOS; specify ontologies in OWL; process ontologies; add semantics to websites using RDFa and "Open Linked Data" standards.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1241, 'en-UK' ,'At the end, students should be able to: know the document lifecycle, be able to identify the various phases and the technologies to be used in each; be able to specify an annotation language for a set of requirements; be able to implement document transformations for various purposes: knowledge extraction, web publishing, information exchange; know and use storage solutions for annotated documents; be able to define the layers necessary to integrate and exchange information between different information systems; be able to implement an electronic publishing project using open international standards: XML, XSLFO and XSL; be able to program the automatic generation of websites from an XML document repository; be able to use annotation languages and respective tools developed by others.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1242, 'en-UK', 'At the end, students should be able to: write scripts to automate a variety of tasks and transformations; solve problems using transformations via regular expressions; understand the advantages and operation of production rule-driven systems (condition-reaction); have the ability to build concrete DSLs; have the ability to build and use corpora; have the ability to extract various information from corpora; have the ability to build electronic dictionaries; have the ability to build small prototypes to model natural language.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1243, 'en-UK', 'Following system programming (from Operating Systems) and the essential notions of concurrent programming and distributed systems (from Distributed Systems), this course covers different paradigms that can be used in the development of sophisticated distributed applications.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1244, 'en-UK' ,'Following on from the basic notions of distributed systems programming and in parallel with the learning of programming paradigms that make it possible to build increasingly complex systems, this course unit aims to focus on reasoning about the distributed system as a whole, understanding the notions of system correctness and the main algorithms for achieving it based on logical clocks and distributed transactions.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1245, 'en-UK' ,'To develop and deepen the training in the area of distributed systems, continuing the development of the techniques studied in the Distributed Systems course unit. The aim is to complement the previous training and to give students the ability to develop reliable distributed systems using software replication techniques for strong consistency.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1246, 'en-UK' ,'This unit builds on the topics developed in Operating Systems and Distributed Systems, and covers a set of topics that support the creation of robust solutions for large-scale distributed systems. Large scale here is understood to mean large numbers of components, potentially distributed on a geographical scale with significant physical distances.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1247, 'en-UK' ,'- Understand the general notions of agent and multi-agent systems, enumerating and classifying different properties of agents and environments;\n - Create agents with a given architecture;\n - Design a society of agents and use it to solve a problem; \n - Develop solutions, in the most diverse areas of application, using an agent-oriented problem solving methodology;\n - Create, in a practical way, a society of agents that communicate using an agent language, and using different platforms.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1248, 'en-UK' ,'- Identify, describe and define the main concepts related to data systems, analytical processing, mining, knowledge extraction and machine learning.\n - Use, classify and evaluate existing or to-be-developed applications.\n - Select the appropriate methodologies and apply available software to solve real-world problems in data analysis, data mining, knowledge extraction and decision making.\n - Know and be able to implement the main algorithms related to data mining techniques, knowledge extraction and forms of learning.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1249, 'en-UK' ,'- Identify, describe and define the main concepts related to Evolutionary Computing (e.g., Virtual Intelligences), Group Intelligence (e.g. “Particle Swarm”) and Natural Computing (e.g. Artificial Neural Networks, Genetic and Evolutionary Programming).\n - Select problem solving methodologies, as well as the computational paradigms that best suit them.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1250, 'en-UK' ,'- Identify, describe and define the main concepts related to Autonomous Systems and Robotic Agents.\n - Implement Autonomous Systems by using the concept of Intelligent Agents.\n - Know and be able to use the knowledge coming from sensors.\n - Know and be able to use the actuators that potentiate mobility and navigation.\n - Study and develop methods of coordination and interaction with the environment.\n - Use prototyping and complexity analysis for their application in problem solving.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1251, 'en-UK' ,'To raise students'' awareness of the added value that can be obtained from the accumulated data resulting from business, public or scientific activities;\n To provide students with the appropriate knowledge so that they can use, or manage the use, with rigor of computational tools to support decision making based on data;\n To provide students with sufficient knowledge, at a conceptual level, so that they can develop and evaluate new data mining tools;');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1252, 'en-UK' ,'A student who successfully completes the course unit should be able to demonstrate that they have acquired the following skills:\n characterize and evaluate qualitatively and quantitatively computing systems;\n analyze, measure and evaluate the performance of computing systems in the execution of applications;\n develop parallel applications capable of running on a wide range of architectures;\n implement applications using the most common types of parallel algorithms;\n measure and optimize the performance of computational applications in order to optimize their performance and scalability;');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1253, 'en-UK' ,'The objective of this course unit is to provide students with the ability to: - understand concepts, strategies, techniques and tools essential for the domain of Information Systems Security;\n - identify and relate the main problems related to threats and technical and non-technical vulnerabilities in the Information Technology domain;\n - understand and apply the standards and best practices in the field of security, both at the level of software development and infrastructure operation;\n - design, implement and maintain protection mechanisms for computer infrastructures;\n - design, implement and maintain mechanisms to mitigate security risks, detect and contain intrusions, and contain the impact on the organization;\n - audit existing infrastructures, identify vulnerabilities, possible exploitation methods and relevant tools;');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1254, 'en-UK', 'Study, understanding and application of Java constructs that enable Functional Programming: Lambdas, Functional Interfaces, Functions, Functional Composition and Currying;\n Study, understanding and application of constructs, techniques and methods of Metaprogramming and Refactoring in Java: Reflection, MetaClasses, Factory Methods, Annotations and Inversion of Control (IoC);\n Massive data processing using pipelines. Study of Java Streams. Operations with streams. Sequential versus parallel processing. Performance analysis and testing.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1255, 'en-UK' ,'Explain the generic techniques for software code analysis;\n Develop tools to analyze programs and software systems;\n Understand the concept of software quality and software quality models;\n Develop metric-based software quality analyzers;\n Build software tools for program transformation, refactoring and evolution.\n Implement fundamental static program analysis algorithms;');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1256, 'en-UK' ,'The course unit aims at learning the process of analyzing the operational requirements of computer applications, followed by the operationalization and evaluation of the entire system supporting the delivery of the service. The course unit has a strong technological character, accompanying the conceptual training of the various topics of the program with the presentation and detailed experimentation of technology representative of the state of the art. The programmatic content of the course unit is particularly aligned with the profiles of Distributed Systems and Applications Engineering. Its practical content is complementary and of manifest interest both for these and for various profiles oriented to the construction of software.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1257, 'en-UK' ,'The Ambient Intelligence course unit aims to provide training in the scientific area of Ambient Intelligence. The topics covered ensure that students will have knowledge about the potential of Ambient Intelligence, its characterization, as well as the most common technologies and problem-solving methodologies in this area, being able to contextualize, apply and analyze them.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1258, 'en-UK' ,'Practical learning of project development concepts, associated with a specialization profile.');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1259, 'en-UK' ,'Design and implement a software project in a group');
INSERT INTO TranslatedTexts(id, language, textValue) VALUES (1260, 'en-UK' ,'The dissertation necessarily implies the involvement of the student in a medium/large scale research and development project. This project is usually inserted in a larger project, associated with a research center and/or a company');
